# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: south-sudan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:south-sudan/1-000-000] In scientific notation, it is written as 1×106 or 106.
[src:south-sudan/1-000-000] Physical quantities can also be expressed using the SI prefix mega (M), when dealing with SI units; for example, 1 megawatt (1 MW) equals 1,000,000 watts.
[src:south-sudan/1-000-000] The meaning of the word "million" is common to the short scale and long scale numbering systems, unlike the larger numbers, which have different names in the two systems.
[src:south-sudan/1-000-000] The million is sometimes used in the English language as a metaphor for a very large number, as in "Not in a million years" and "You're one in a million", or a hyperbole, as in "I've walked a million miles" and "You've asked a million-dollar question".
[src:south-sudan/1-000-000] Even though it is often stressed that counting to precisely a million would be an exceedingly tedious task due to the time and concentration required, there are many ways to bring the number "down to size" in approximate quantities, ignoring irregularities or packing effects.
[src:south-sudan/1-000-000] In Indian English and Pakistani English, it is also expressed as 10 lakh.
[src:south-sudan/1-000-000] Lakh is derived from *lakṣa* for 100,000 in Sanskrit.
[src:south-sudan/1-000-000] There are 78,498 primes less than 106, where 999,983 is the largest prime number smaller than 1,000,000.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] The **11th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 11 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, South Asia, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 12 hours, 46 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 29 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] In Thailand, a 1966 cabinet resolution restricts the rights of non-Thai companies to conduct mineral exploration or mining operations north of this parallel.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] The border between Ghana and what was then French Upper Volta (now Burkina Faso) was fixed by treaty between the French and British at the Conference of Paris in 1898, to be the 11th parallel.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] The border does not follow the boundary exactly, but follows it approximately, crossing over it several times.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] The **12th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 12 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 12 hours, 50 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 25 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] The **13th parallel north** is a circle of latitude 13 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, Asia, the Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, the Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] At this latitude, the sun is visible for 12 hours 53 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours 22 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] The **14th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 14 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 12 hours, 57 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 18 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] The **15th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 15 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] It crosses the Saharan fringe (the Sahel) in Africa, three key peninsulas of Asia (between which parts of the Indian Ocean), the Pacific Ocean, an isthmus of Central America, the southern Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] In the Chadian-Libyan conflict of 1978 to 1987, its intra-Chad part came to be known as the "Red Line", separating opposing combatants, above all in Operation Manta.
[src:south-sudan/13th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 13 hours, 1 minute during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 14 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] A referendum took place in Southern Sudan from 9 to 15 January 2011, on whether the region should remain a part of Sudan or become independent.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The referendum was one of the consequences of the 2005 Naivasha Agreement between the Khartoum central government and the Sudan People's Liberation Army/Movement (SPLA/M).
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] A simultaneous referendum was supposed to be held in Abyei on whether to become part of South Sudan but it was postponed due to conflict over demarcation and residency rights.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] On 7 February 2011, the referendum commission published the final results, with a landslide majority of 98.83% voting in favour of independence.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] While the ballots were suspended in 10 of the 79 counties for exceeding 100% of the voter turnout, the number of votes was still well over the requirement of 60% turnout, and the majority vote for secession is not in question.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The predetermined date for the creation of an independent state was 9 July 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The prerequisites for the referendum included a census, which was used to define how wealth and political power will be apportioned between regions.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The census was the basis of a voter registration process, which was also used for the national elections in 2010, which in turn set the stage for the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Problems included disagreements between the north and south over what they were obliged to do by the Naivasha Agreement, funding difficulties and an enormous logistical challenge.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In the south, unmapped minefields from the war continued to make movement difficult, while up to 5,000,000 Sudanese were nomadic.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Up to 2,000,000 internally displaced persons from the south remained in camps around Khartoum, in the centre of the country, whilst refugees remained in Uganda and Kenya.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] A further complication resulted from the conflict in Darfur to the west, where civilians who had fled attacks refused to take part in census out of fear that the government would use the results against them.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Darfuri rebel groups were unanimous in their denunciation of the planned census, while the Justice and Equality Movement group had threatened to attack any census-taker.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Modest progress was made in early September 2010, but disagreements on fundamental points remained.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] It is envisaged that "popular consultations" in South Kordofan and Blue Nile, without a clear reference to referendums and/or independence, would raise concerns about the future of these regions.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] According to the terms of the Comprehensive Peace Agreement (or CPA), in October 2009, the central government of Sudan and the South Sudanese government agreed that turnout would have to be at least 60% of 3,800,000 voters would be necessary to validate.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In this case, a simple majority vote in favour of independence would result in secession for South Sudan; should the turnout be insufficient in the first referendum, a second one will be held within sixty days.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Sudanese officials have said throughout campaigning that, regardless of their pro-unity or pro-separatist stance, the ultimate aim was a peaceful transition.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Vice President Kiir acknowledged his administration had failed to deliver "the dividends of peace", and noted that a campaign to confiscate arms was a solution to maintaining stability.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Sudan's President Omar al-Bashir said that the southern region had a right to choose to secede and that the referendum was helpful because unity "could not be forced by power." He also said he would respect the outcome of the vote and support the south.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] However, he also said that though secession was a right it may not resolve issues for the south: "The stability of the south is very important to us because any instability in the south will have an impact on the north.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] If there is a war in your neighbour's house, you will not be at peace.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Negotiations continue between the ruling parties in the north and south on potential post-referendum arrangements—looking at future issues such as citizenship, security, finance and wealth sharing.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Deng said he fears that an immediate budget cut for the north would ignite a war.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] "In order to avoid conflict, we could look to a phase-out arrangement whereby you provide the north some [oil] until they get an alternative".
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The pipeline to export southern oil currently cuts through the north, and the south has not begun construction on a pipeline that would avoid that route.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In an article published by *The Washington Post* on 21 September 2010, Deng noted that an interim agreement could help both north and south and result in a "win-win".
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The northern government said it would assume most of the country's $38,000,000,000 debt if secession was voted upon.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] National campaigns were being held by both parties to address issues of potential clashes ahead of the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] President Al-Bashir wanted to reassure and assuage tension surrounding the issue of citizenship rights in the case of South Sudan secession.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] On 8 January, the mood in Juba, the southern capital, and the wider region was said to be jubilant with final pro-secession rallies celebrating independence in advance.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Early during the referendum process, an Egyptian proposal was made to have a confederation between the north and south of the country.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] However, President Omar al-Bashir said it was not being considered because the issue of the referendum was about "unity or separation.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Our brothers in the south are refusing at the moment the proposal of confederation.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi later went to Sudan to try to assuage the conflict, though both men had previously called for the country to stay united.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Egypt's Foreign Minister Ahmed Aboul Gheit said the meeting sought to ensure the referendum could be held in a "climate of freedom, transparency, and credibility, reflecting the will of the sons of the south" and also that both the South and North could strengthen bonds.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Observers and key players feared violence ahead of the South Sudan referendum for a variety of reasons.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Talks on resolving the status and of the eligibility criteria for voters in the disputed Abyei region broke down in October 2010, although both the central ruling NCP and southern SPLM said their respective teams "will meet again in Ethiopia toward the end of October to continue their discussions.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Didiri Mohammad Ahmad, an NCP official, said it was "not possible" to hold the referendum on the future of Abyei on time, and it could be delayed for months or be settled without a vote.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Sudan's Defense Minister, Abdel Rahim Mohammed Hussein, suggested the vote may have to be postponed.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] "According to the reality on the ground...border issues and Abyei must be resolved within the framework of one nation because doing so in the framework of two countries open[s] the door for foreign interference.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The referendum is not a goal but a tool to consolidate and promote security and stability.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The government Sudan asked the UN for the printing of ballots for the referendum as diplomats and the electoral commission warned of any further delay would miss the deadline to hold the election.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Bishtina Mohammed El Salam of the Misseriya, who dominate the region along with the Dinka tribe, said he would not accept Abyei's seceding and joining the south even though the latter favored secession.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] "If the Dinka take this decision – to annex Abyei to the south – there will be an immediate war without any excuse.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] We think they should be reasonable and think about it.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The status of the Nuba Mountains region of South Kurdufan and Blue Nile is more complex as ethnic data is less clear.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In the Blue Nile, African ethnic groups such as the Berta, Anuak and Koma are dominant in the South.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The Northern part, however, has an Arab majority, although the enclave of Ingessana in Tabi Hills is mostly Animist and was targeted by the northern forces during the civil war.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The total population stands at 832,112 according to the Election Commission.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] During the 2010 provincial elections, the NCP won 29 out of the 48 seats, while the SPLM won 17 seats.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In the National Assembly elections, the NCP won 6 out of the 10 seats, while the SPLM got 4.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] However, the SPLM accused the NCP of fraud.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The separate gubernatorial election was won by the SPLM candidate, who polled almost 5% votes more than his NCP rival.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The Nuba Mountain was home to some 1,000,000 ethnic Nuba during 1980.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] A total of 99 different tribes used to live in this region.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] When the civil war broke out during the late 1980s, the Nuba aligned with the SPLA.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The vast majority of Nuba were taken as prisoners of war and forcibly relocated to camps in North Kordofan and Khartoum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] When the fighting ended, only about half the population survived.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The rest either surrendered and moved north or were killed during the fighting.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] After the signing of the peace accord, some of the Nuba returned to the mountains, but the tribal elders refused to re-admit them into the tribes as they feared the abductees (mostly young men) were too Islamised.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] They were finally allowed back into the tribal fold after a 6-month re-education camp.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The SPLA controls four counties in Southern Kordofan: Lagawa, Kadugli, Rashad and Dilling.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In 2005, the Arab dominated West Kordofan was merged in to South Kordofan, resulting in Arabs gaining a majority in the new province.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The 2008 census reported the total population of South Kordofan at 1,406,404 (though the SPLA claims many ethnic Nuba living in remote regions were not counted).
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] This figure includes the Abyei region and it is not known how many are Nuba, Ngok and Baggara.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] During the 2010 National Assembly election, the NCP won 13 out of the 17 seats, while the SPLM won 4 seats.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The gubernatorial elections were postponed to 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] During the 2010 Presidential elections, the NCP received 69.3% of the votes in South Kordofan and 56.6% in the Blue Nile, while the SPLM received 18.5% of the votes in South Kordofan and 32.7% in the Blue Nile.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Ahmed Harun of NCP defeated Abdelaziz al-Hilu of the SPLM in the 2011 South Kordofan Gubernatorial elections.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Harun received 201,455 votes compared to Hilu's 194,955 votes.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] NCP won 33 seats in the legislature to SPLM's 22 seats.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] SPLM refused to acknowledge the results, accusing the NCP of voter intimidation and electoral fraud.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Religion was also expected to significantly influence the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] South Sudanese Muslims supported secession.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] President Omar al-Bashir said dual citizenship would not be allowed.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] According to the CPA, 20 percent of civil service jobs were reserved for southerners, which would then be lost if the country splits.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Questions were also asked about the status of tribes such as the Nuba and Misseriya of South Kordofan that inhabit the border regions with South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] When questioned in a poll prior to the official referendum, 97% of South Sudanese people said that they would be voting for independence.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] An early poll of 1,400 individuals was carried out by a coalition of civil society organisations in Southern Sudan prior to the January referendum, indicating that 97% of voters would likely vote for secession.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] According to John Andruga, chairman of the coalition, 100% of respondents in the states of Unity and Eastern Equatoria would vote for secession.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] A similar survey carried out one year prior by the US-based National Democratic Institute had indicated that 90% of voters would vote for secession.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Authorities in both the north and south of Sudan have been accused of harassment and intimidation against the media in order to avoid dissenting coverage.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Rights groups warned the media could be slapped with further restrictions.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] He also said that the potential borders between them would have to be drawn up pending redeployment of the SPLM's forces to the 1956 border.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Sudan's president, Omar Hassan al-Bashir, accused the SPLM of breaching the terms of the peace deal and warned of a return to conflict if the disputes were not settled before the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Despite that, he said he was committed to holding the referendum, but insisted on settling differences over the shared border and how to share the oil, debt and Nile river water.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The NCP accused the SPLM of discouraging southerners who were living in the north of the country from registering, as the SPLM threatened not to recognize the referendum if its demands were not met.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Southerners in the North were reluctant to vote because of fears of being uprooted from their homes.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Muslims in the border provinces of the South also expressed fear of a campaign of violence that could be unleashed as a consequence of the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Many feared a return to civil war, should the referendum fail because of the increasingly heated rhetoric.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Along with Chad, Sudan sought to secure the border area ahead of the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In addition to warnings of civil war, it was also read that a possible civil war could involve the Lord's Resistance Army and bring Uganda into the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Despite rifts amongst Southern parties, more than 20 parties ironed over their differences to put a show of unity before the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The United States extended sanctions against Sudan on 1 November 2010 in order to pressure the government to stick to the referendum deadline.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The US then offered to drop Sudan from a US list of state-sponsors of terrorism if the two referendums were held on time and the results were respected.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] They again partook in a statement before the referendum in lauding al-Bashir's statement to respect the vote.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Following concerns from the UN about delays, representatives of both regions affirmed a commitment to hold the referendum on time; a media campaign was also launched to raise awareness and increase the turnout.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Minni Minnawi, the only Sudan Liberation Army faction signatory to the Darfur Peace Agreement, quit the agreement and resigned his post as Special Advisor to the President, saying the deal had failed.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] He consequently moved to Juba in the south saying the referendum would be successful as southerners "reject the policy of this [Khartoum] government" and the north would then be a "failed state." In return, the government declared Minnawi an "enemy" and closed his Khartoum office.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In December 2010, the Constitutional Court agreed to carry out an investigation into a petition filed by local lawyers seeking the dissolution of the electoral body that was organizing the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Despite calls from the government in southern Sudan that northerners living in the south should be protected, some northerners who were uncertain of their future in an independent state started heading north.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Two days prior to the vote, David Yau Yau's militia and the SPLA clashed outside Pibor.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Questions were asked if a positive vote on the referendum would set a precedent for other secessionist movements on the African continent.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Citing these examples, it asked where such a precedent for secession could lead: East Sudan and Darfur, Nigeria or South Africa.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] President Jimmy Carter, former United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former Tanzanian Prime Minister Joseph Warioba led the Carter Center international observation delegation.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] US Senator John Kerry, Chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, visited Southern Sudan three times during the referendum period, including during polling.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Actor George Clooney, who is supporting the Satellite Sentinel Project (using satellites as a conflict early warning system for Sudan), also made visits to Sudan during the referendum period.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Several major regional organisations deployed international observers, including the African Union, the European Union, the League of Arab States and the Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD).
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] These organisations issued a joint press statement on the first day of polling.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Domestic observation organisations also deployed Sudanese men and women to observe the process, these included the Sudanese Network for Democratic Elections (SuNDE), the Sudan Domestic Elections Monitoring Programme (SuDEMOP) and the Sudanese Group for Democracy and Elections (SuGDE).
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Other national civil society organisations were also accredited as observers.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Normally, the UN does not deploy electoral observers, however, in response to a request from the parties of the CPA, the United Nations Secretary-General's Panel on the Referenda in Sudan was established.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The panel is composed of three senior officials, former Tanzania President Benjamin Mkapa, former Minister of Foreign Affairs of Portugal António Monteiro, and Bhojraj Pokharel, a former Chairman of the Election Commission of Nepal, who are appointed by and report to the UN Secretary-General.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The panel made periodic visits to Sudan during the referendum period and is supported by field reporting officers and stakeholder-observer liaison officers.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Registration for the vote started on 15 November with Salva Kiir's appeal for registering en masse.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Many of those who fled South Sudan during the civil war returned in the months and weeks leading up to the referendum, with some southern politicians trying to have them play a role in swinging the vote towards independence.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Almost four million citizens registered before the deadline on 5 December; as the stream of returnees continued unabated, however, many arrived too late to register for the referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Voting on the referendum began on 9 January 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] On 12 January, after three days of voting, representatives of the SPLA/M announced that, according to their estimates, the 60 percent turnout threshold required for the referendum's validity (corresponding to around 2.3 million voters) had been reached.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Official confirmation came later the same day when the referendum commission released a statement announcing that turnout would "exceed" the required 60 percent threshold.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Jimmy Carter expressed his belief on 13 January that the referendum would likely meet international standards for both the conduct of the vote and freedom of voters.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The United Nations reported that preliminary results would be expected by 2 February 2011, with final results expected within the following two weeks.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] According to preliminary counts reviewed by the Associated Press, consisting of 30,000 ballots in 10 polling stations, the sample had a 95% turnout with 96% in favour of secession, 3% in favour of unity and the rest invalid.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Mohamed Ibrahim Khalil, chairman of the referendum commission, said 83 percent of eligible voters in the south and 53 percent in the north had voted.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The South Sudan Referendum Commission affirmed the validity of the vote, however the vote was still ongoing at the time.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] As voting ended, Sudan again vowed to recognise the result.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Southerners living in Darfur were given the opportunity to vote in the referendum from special polling stations as some tribes advocated unity and others supported separation with possible ominous precedence for Darfur itself.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Polling stations were also set up in eight countries with large South Sudanese populations, namely Australia, Canada, Egypt, Ethiopia, Kenya, Uganda, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] In the United States, where an estimated 25,000 to 50,000 South Sudanese nationals reside, polling booths were opened in eight states: Virginia, Massachusetts, Illinois, Texas, Tennessee, Nebraska, Arizona and Washington.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Similar polling booths were set up in the Canadian cities of Calgary and Toronto, to cater to the South Sudanese community there; an estimated 40,000 to 50,000 Sudanese live in Canada, about 2,200 of whom had registered to vote in either of the two cities.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Members of the South Sudanese diaspora have been split as to their support for or against separation; members of some tribes advocate unity, while members of other tribes supported separation.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Several days before voting began, the SPLA/M and a rebel faction led by Lieutenant General George Athor in Jonglei State agreed to a ceasefire agreement after nearly a year of fighting, meaning a halt to military operations, troop movement and recruitment by either side.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The agreement was seen as important for a "peaceful voting environment".
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The day before voting began, at least six people were killed in clashes between South Sudan security forces and a pro-Khartoum Sudan militia in Unity state.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] One person was also killed in clashes between the Misseriya tribe and police in Abyei.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The SPLA/M said the fighting started a day earlier because of the Misseriya.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] One day into the vote, on 10 January, a further 6 people were killed in clashes near Abyei, bringing the total to 30 dead in that region.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] As of 15 January, Radio France Internationale reported that the Sudanese central government in Khartoum had begun to recall ambassadors named by the SPLA as part of the CPA and had stopped shipping material for passports to Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Sudan also became the first state to recognize South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] President of the United States Barack Obama said the result of the vote was "inspiring" as voters decided "their own future [and marked] another step forward in Africa's long journey toward justice and democracy".
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] He also said that the United States would recognize South Sudan's independence when it is formalized in July.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Salva Kiir met the leaders of the Polisario Front Mohamed Abdelaziz at an African Union summit.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Abdel-Aziz congratulated Kiir for on a successful referendum process.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] He lauded "the wisdom and courage" of people of South Sudan people for a peaceful resolution of the conflict and expressed his hope that post-referendum arrangements and agreements could be finishing in the interim period before statehood.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] He also briefed Kiir of the Western Sahara's process to a similar referendum.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The precedence of the vote was seen as important because most African states' borders were decided during colonial times which resulted in a heterogeneous mix of religions, ethnicities, and cultures.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The Organisation of African Unity, however, refrained from redrawing boundaries for the fear that wars of secession could be sparked.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] New names for an independent country were being suggested, with South Sudan being controversial as it does not offer a break from Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Over 12 names had been suggested, including: Nile Republic, Jubian Republic, Kush Republic and Azania.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The SPLM proposed naming the country South Sudan, with Nile Republic, Jubian Republic, Kush Republic as other possibilities.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The country was then officially named the Republic of South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] Amongst the issues to be handled by a new government are job creation.
[src:south-sudan/2011-south-sudanese-independence-referendum] The Minister of Cooperatives and Rural Development Jimmy Lemi Milla was shot dead in his office along with his bodyguard in an apparent personal feud.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The **Heglig Crisis** was a brief war fought between the countries of Sudan and South Sudan in 2012 over oil-rich regions between South Sudan's Unity and Sudan's South Kordofan states.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudan invaded and briefly occupied the small border town of Heglig before being pushed back by the Sudanese army.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Small-scale clashes continued until an agreement on borders and natural resources was signed on 26 September, resolving most aspects of the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Prior to independence from Sudan two civil wars were fought in the region from 1955 to 1972 and from 1983 to 2005, in which 2.5 million people were killed and more than 5 million externally displaced.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudan peacefully gained independence from Sudan on 9 July 2011 with Sudan's long-term president Omar al-Bashir promising to "work with our southern brothers and help them set up their state".
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Despite this relations between the two states have been marked by conflict over the disputed oil-rich Abyei region.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In January 2012, South Sudan shut down all of its oil fields over a disagreement with oil transit fees imposed by Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In May 2011, it was reported that Sudan had seized control of Abyei, with a force of approximately 5,000 soldiers after three days of clashes with South Sudanese forces.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The precipitating factor was an ambush by South Sudanese forces on May 19 which killed 22 northern soldiers.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The northern advance included shelling, aerial bombardment and numerous tanks.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Following the advance South Sudan withdrew its forces from Abyei and declared the movement of Sudanese forces into Abyei to be an "act of war".
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The United Nations sent an envoy to Khartoum to intervene.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] A deal on militarization was reached on 20 June 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The United Nations Interim Security Force for Abyei, consisting of Ethiopian troops were deployed under a UNSC resolution from 27 June 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In early December 2011, Jau, a town in Unity state in South Sudan, was occupied by Sudanese forces.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In early March 2012, the Sudanese Air Force bombed parts of Pariang county.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Both countries accused each other of supporting rebels on their soil as part of the ongoing internal conflicts in Sudan and South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 26 March, the Republic of Sudan claimed that South Sudan attacked the Heglig oilfield, located in the Sudanese state of South Kordofan, while South Sudan claimed that their forces had carried out an operation within the borders of South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The South Sudanese attack was supported by the Sudanese rebel group JEM, which attacked from South Sudanese state of Unity.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The following day, the Sudanese Air Force launched a bombing raid on the Unity oilfield in Unity, located to the north of the state capital, Bentiu.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The Sudanese Army later attacked the disputed areas of Jau, Pan Akuach, and Teshwin, but were repelled by the South Sudanese Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA).
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudanese artillery positions 20 kilometres north of Bentiu, which had been involved in the shelling of Heglig, were bombarded by artillery from the northern side of the border.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudan's Information Minister, Abdallah Ali Masar, confirmed that South Sudanese had penetrated 10 km into Sudanese territory, but also claimed that Sudanese forces had repelled them and driven them back, and had taken several prisoners.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudan's forces withdrew from the disputed area on 28 March.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 31 March, Sudanese warplanes bombed the Southern forces positions on the border, although officials from the north said it was artillery, not aircraft involved in the attack.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudan claimed to have shot down a Sudanese MiG-29 warplane on 4 April over Unity during an air raid in which Sudanese planes bombed an oil pipeline in South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The Sudanese government denied any aerial bombings had taken place and called the accusations "fabrications" by South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The SPLA claimed that Teshwin in South Sudan had been attacked by Sudanese forces on 9 April with battle going on into the next day The town of Abiemnhom in Unity was reportedly attacked by two brigades from the Sudanese army, which South Sudan claimed was an attempt to seize its oil fields.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] At least four civilians were injured in the clashes, although there were no immediate reports of military casualties on either side.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The South's government said that northern forces had breached the border accompanied by militias, but had been repelled.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] A Sudanese military spokesman later admitted that the Sudanese army had been defeated during a battle at Heglig and was forced to retreat northwards.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] There were some reports that the fighting had broken out after Sudanese forces attempted to retake a border post lost to Southern forces two weeks previous.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 10 April Colonel Khalid Sawarmi, spokesman for the Sudanese army, claimed that South Sudanese forces had taken control of the Heglig oil fields and the town of Heglig itself, marking the start of the Second Battle of Heglig.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In this second capture of Heglig the SPLA was again supported by the JEM.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The Sudanese government said on 11 April that heavy fighting continued along the disputed border areas and the Sudanese army was reported to be trying to retake Heglig with Sudan announcing that they would use all legitimate means to retake the oil fields.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudan said that they were holding defensive positions in Heglig, awaiting a Sudanese counterattack.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Second Vice President of Sudan, al-Haj Adam Youssef, stated that Sudan was now in a state declared that all negotiations between the two states were on hold.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The next day, on 12 April, the Sudanese Air Force bombed Bentiu, in an attempt to destroy a strategic bridge using an Antonov An-26 transport plane converted into an improvised bomber, killing one South Sudanese soldier.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The parliaments of both countries called for a mobilisation of their respective armed forces.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudan also began a general mobilisation of its armed forces as South Sudanese forces penetrated as far as 70 kilometres into Sudanese territory, according to Rahmatullah Mohamed Osman, Under Secretary for the Foreign Ministry of Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Following the capture of Heglig, the Government of Sudan announced that their forces withdrawn to Khersana where they were reportedly preparing to retake Heglig.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] It was at some point in April that Salva Kiir, President of South Sudan and his advisors organized an all-volunteer militia –Mathiang Anyoor– to aid the SPLA in fighting the Sudanese during this conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The militia later transformed into a private army and became infamous for committing numerous atrocities during the subsequent South Sudanese Civil War.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudanese forces began reinforcing their positions in Heglig on 13 April, whilst Sudan continued to mobilise its own forces.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] According to the South Sudanese government, the frontlines had remained static during the day.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudanese forces claimed to be advancing on Heglig and that the situation would be dealt with "within hours." A spokesman of the Sudanese government said that its army was on the outskirts of Heglig, while South Sudan's government said that it would defend themselves if attacked.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudan's vice president Reik Machar said a Sudanese attempt to retake Heglig by force was halted 30 km north of the town.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudan claimed to have destroyed two tanks during the clashes.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The Sudanese air force, operating two Sukhoi Su-25 jets, reportedly bombed Jau and Panakuach, as well as Heglig once again, killing five civilians.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 14 April, South Sudanese forces continued to advance northwards, and repelled a Sudanese counterattack on Khersana.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Southern troops moved to close all three roads to Heglig on 14 April.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] It was also reported that most facilities in Heglig had been damaged during the fighting.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Two MiG-29s from the Sudanese Air Force attempted to destroy a bridge in Bentiu but missed their target and ended up killing four civilians and a soldier and wounding five others.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The attack was widely believed to be an attempt to damage South Sudanese supply lines.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudanese army units were reported to have reached a few kilometres from Heglig and that they were fighting with South Sudanese forces.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudan's military spokesman Al-Sawarmi Khalid revealed that their immediate objective was to "destroy the South's war machine", rather than enter Heglig itself.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] South Sudan disputed the north's version of events as propaganda, claiming that northern forces were still 30 kilometres (19 miles) from Heglig.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 15 April, the Sudan People's Liberation Army spokesman Philip Aguer claimed that after overnight clashes in Kelet South Sudan held on to its positions and destroyed two Sudanese tanks.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudan shelled the western part of South Sudan's Upper Nile state during 15 April, in an apparent attempt to open up a new front.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudanese troops crossed the border into South Sudan's Upper Nile state and briefly occupied the small town of Kuek, before being expelled by South Sudan's army.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 16 April, Sudan's parliament met and voted unanimously to declare that "South Sudan is an enemy of all Sudanese state agencies".
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The parliamentary speaker called for Sudan to mobilise all its resources to fight South Sudan and topple their government.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Rabie Abdelaty, a spokesman for the Sudanese government, ruled out peace talks with the South, saying it would hurt national pride if Sudan did not take back Heglig by force.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 18 April, a new front opened up in the conflict, 160 kilometres (99 mi) west of Heglig, resulting in seven South Sudanese soldiers and 15 Sudanese soldiers being killed.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The clash was reportedly sparked when a South Sudanese soldier was shot dead when collecting water near the road between Aweil and Meiram.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On April 20 Salva Kiir ordered his forces to withdraw from Heglig.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On the day the Sudanese army entered Heglig with al-Bashir holding a victory rally in Khartoum.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On the 22 April, more fighting broke out along the whole border as Sudanese soldiers backed by tanks and artillery launched three waves of attacks 10 kilometres (6 mi) into South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] At least one South Sudanese soldier was killed and two wounded in the attack.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudan bombed the town of Rubkona on 23 April, damaging several market stalls, in an attempt to destroy a bridge between Rubkona and neighbouring Bentiu.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] At least three people were killed in the raid.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The following day, Kiir stated on a visit to China that Sudan had "declared war" on South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudan and South Sudan restarted negotiations in June 2012 under mediation by the African Union's envoy Thabo Mbeki.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 27 September, Omar al-Bashir and Salva Kiir signed eight agreements in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, which led the way to resume important oil exports and create a 10 km (6 mi) demilitarised zone along their border.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The agreements allows for the return of 350,000 barrels of South Sudanese oil to the world market.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In addition, the agreements include an understanding on the parameters to follow in regards to demarcating their border, an economic-cooperation agreement and a deal to protect each other's citizens.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Certain issues remained unsolved and future talks were scheduled to resolve them.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Vice President Riek Machar outlined what agreements were signed, but lamented the lack of a resolution on Abyei.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon commended the two leaders on reaching an agreement.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Ethiopian Prime Minister Hailemariam Desalegn also praised the outcome and hoped it would build momentum.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In mid-March 2013, both countries began to withdraw their forces from the border area in a bid to creating a demilitarised buffer zone and resume South Sudanese oil production for export through Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In early April South Sudanese oil started to flow through pipelines in Sudan again.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 10 June Kiir accused al-Bashir of mobilising for war after al-Bashir threatened to cut oil transit through his country with Kiir stating that he would not go to war over the oil transit issue.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In October 2013, al-Bashir visited Juba to discuss the measures with Kiir.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] He was warmly welcomed and said that progress had been made.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Kiir said that he was looking to mend relations with Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The Sudanese Army is equipped with predominantly Chinese and Soviet-made weapons while Sudan People's Liberation Army weapons vary, having few vehicles and mostly small arms.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The following table should not be considered exhaustive.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The conflict had, by 14 April, forced over 100,000 people to flee their homes.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Indiscriminate bombings and ground attacks by Sudanese forces on civilian areas, particularly in the Nuba Mountains, resulted in numerous deaths and injuries.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudanese national radio announced that the President of Sudan, Omar al-Bashir, would suspend his planned visit to the South Sudanese capital, Juba, as a result of the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] A summit between the leaders of the two countries had been planned to be held in Juba some time in April 2012, following up from the meeting of the political, military, and security committee of the African Union on 30 March in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] A meeting between South Sudan and Sudan on the subject of the disputed region of Abyei scheduled to have been held on 22 March had previously been postponed by Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 11 April, Second Vice President of Sudan, Al-Haj Adam stated that Sudan was now in a state of war and declared that all negotiations between the two states were on hold.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 16 April, Sudan's parliament met and voted unanimously to declare that "South Sudan is an enemy of all Sudanese state agencies" The parliamentary speaker called for Sudan to mobilise all its resources to fight South Sudan and topple their government.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Rabie Abdelaty, a spokesman for the Government of Sudan, ruled out peace talks with the south, saying it would hurt national pride if Sudan did not take back Heglig by force.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Sudan began a general mobilisation of its armed forces as South Sudanese forces penetrated as far as 70 kilometres into Sudanese territory, according to Rahmatullah Mohamed Osman, Under Secretary for the Foreign Ministry.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] During Friday prayers on 13 April in Sudan, some sermons in Khartoum condemned the South Sudanese capture of Heglig, while television broadcasts included *jihadi* and patriotic songs.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Following South Sudan's withdrawal from Heglig, President Omar al-Bashir declared that there would be no negotiations with the "poisonous insects" in reference to the South Sudanese.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The President of South Sudan, Salva Kiir, suggested that Sudan was responsible for initiating the conflict, and that further clashes could lead to war: "This morning [the Sudanese] air force came and bombed areas in Unity state.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Fuel supplies began to run out in some filling stations in Juba around 15 April as huge queues of motorists tried to fill up as panic buying set in.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 27 March, a spokesman for Ban Ki-moon, the Secretary-General of the United Nations, called for the two countries to end the conflict and "use to the fullest extent existing political and security mechanisms to peacefully address their differences".
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 23 April 2012, Ban Ki-moon condemned Sudan's bombing of border areas in South Sudan, demanding Khartoum cease all hostilities "as a matter of urgency".
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 15 April 2012, the Arab Parliament called on South Sudan for restraint and to withdraw from the town of Heglig.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] A statement signed by Arab Parliament head Salem Deqbasi said that the Arab Parliament's bureau called on South Sudan to "heed the voice of reason" and immediately pull its forces out of the areas it had occupied inside Sudanese territory, including Heglig.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 26 April, the Arab League escalated its rhetoric, condemning South Sudan's "aggression" and saying Heglig belongs to Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The Arab League went further to say it supported Sudan's "right to defend itself", and condemned South Sudan's alleged support of rebels in Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 25 April 2012, the African Union condemned Sudan's bombing of parts of South Sudan, and called on both sides to cease all hostilities.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The Peace and Security Council also put forth a 7-point roadmap in which the two sides would be given two weeks to restart negotiations.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The AU urged both sides to refrain from "inflammatory statements and propaganda that could fuel the conflict".
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] In March an Iranian surveillance drone crashed in Sudan after being fired upon by South Sudanese-backed rebels.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] Israel allegedly airlifted military hardware to the South Sudanese armed forces "on a daily basis" during the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 27 March 2012, the President of Kenya, Mwai Kibaki, suggested that Kenya could mediate between the two countries, stating "Kenya is keen on good and stable relations between the two countries".
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] On 6 May 2012, Africa Minister Henry Bellingham supported the African Union-led initiative, calling for both sides to restart negotiations and comply with the ceasefire.
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] To South Sudan, the US release recognized the "right of South Sudan to self-defense", but urged "restraint in its reaction to Sudan’s attack in Unity State".
[src:south-sudan/2012-south-sudan-sudan-border-conflict] The US welcomed the South Sudanese withdrawal from Heglig and called for all South Sudanese troops to be withdrawn from areas across the 1 January 1956 border.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The **2012 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXX Olympiad** and also known as **London 2012**, were an international multi-sport event held from 27 July to 12 August 2012 in London, England.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Some events were held at venues elsewhere in the United Kingdom.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There were 10,518 athletes from 206 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) who participated in the 2012 Olympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Following a bid headed by the former Olympic champion Sebastian Coe and the mayor of London, Ken Livingstone, London was selected as the host city at the 117th IOC Session in Singapore on 6 July 2005, defeating bids from Moscow, New York City, Madrid and Paris.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London became the first city to host the modern Olympics three times, having previously hosted the Summer Games in 1908 and 1948.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Construction for the Games involved considerable redevelopment, with an emphasis on sustainability.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The main focus was a new 200-hectare (490-acre) Olympic Park, constructed on a former industrial site in Stratford, East London.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Games also used venues that already existed before the bid.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The United States topped the medal table, winning the most gold medals (48) and the highest number of medals overall (105).
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] China finished second with a total of 91 medals (38 gold) and Great Britain came third with 65 medals overall (29 gold).
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Michael Phelps of the United States became the most decorated Olympic athlete of all time, winning his 22nd medal.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Brunei entered female athletes for the first time, meaning that every currently eligible country has now sent a female competitor to at least one Olympic Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Women's boxing was included for the first time, and the 2012 Games became the first at which every sport had female competitors.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Games received considerable praise for their organisation, with the volunteers, the British military and public enthusiasm commended particularly highly.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were described as happy and glorious.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony, directed by the Academy Award winner Danny Boyle, received widespread acclaim.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Belgian Jacques Rogge, who was succeeded by German Thomas Bach the next year.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London was chosen over Birmingham to represent Great Britain's bid by the British Olympic Association.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] By 15 July 2003—the deadline for interested cities to submit bids to the International Olympic Committee (IOC)—nine cities had submitted bids to host the 2012 Summer Olympics: Havana, Istanbul, Leipzig, London, Madrid, Moscow, New York City, Paris and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 18 May 2004, as a result of a scored technical evaluation, the IOC reduced the number of cities to five: London, Madrid, Moscow, New York and Paris.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] All five submitted their candidate files by 19 November 2004 and were visited by the IOC inspection team during February and March 2005.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Paris bid suffered two setbacks during the IOC inspection visit: a number of strikes and demonstrations coinciding with the visits, and a report that a key member of the bid team, Guy Drut, would face charges over alleged corrupt party political finances.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Throughout the process, Paris was widely seen as the favourite, particularly as this was its third bid in recent years.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London was initially seen as lagging behind Paris by a considerable margin.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Its position began to improve after the appointment of Lord Coe as the new chair of the London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (LOCOG) on 19 May 2004.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In late August 2004, reports predicted a tie between London and Paris.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 6 June 2005 the IOC released its evaluation reports for the five candidate cities.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] They did not contain any scores or rankings, but the report for Paris was considered the most positive.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London was close behind, having closed most of the gap observed by the initial evaluation in 2004.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] New York and Madrid also received very positive evaluations.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 1 July 2005, when asked who would win, Jacques Rogge said, "I cannot predict it since I don't know how the IOC members will vote.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] But my gut feeling tells me that it will be very close.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 6 July 2005 the final selection was announced at the 117th IOC Session in Singapore.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Moscow was the first city to be eliminated, followed by New York and Madrid.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The final two contenders were London and Paris.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of the fourth round of voting, London won the right to host the 2012 Games with 54 votes to 50.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The celebrations in London were short-lived, being overshadowed by bombings on London's transport system less than 24 hours after the announcement.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Five years after the games, Paris would later be selected to host the 2024 Summer Olympics on 13 September 2017.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The London Organising Committee of the Olympic Games (LOCOG) was created to oversee the staging of the Games, and held its first board meeting on 3 October 2005.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The committee, chaired by Lord Coe, was in charge of implementing and staging the Games, while the Olympic Delivery Authority (ODA), established in April 2006, was in charge of construction of the venues and infrastructure.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Government Olympic Executive (GOE), a unit within the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS), was the lead government body for coordinating the London 2012 Olympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It focused on oversight of the Games, cross-programme management, and the London 2012 Olympic Legacy before and after the Games that would benefit London and the wider United Kingdom.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The organisation was also responsible for the supervision of the £9.3 billion of public sector funding.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In August 2011 security concerns arose surrounding the hosting of the Olympic Games in London, following the 2011 England riots.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Some countries expressed safety concerns, despite the IOC's assurance that the riots would not affect the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC's Coordination Commission for the 2012 Games completed its tenth and final visit to London in March 2012.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Its members concluded that "London is ready to host the world this summer".
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Facilities of the 2012 Summer Olympics in the Greater London area.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games used a mixture of new venues, existing and historic facilities, and temporary facilities, some of them in well-known locations such as Hyde Park and Horse Guards Parade.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] After the Games, some of the new facilities would be reused in their Olympic form, while others were resized or relocated.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The majority of venues were divided into three zones within Greater London: the Olympic Zone, the River Zone and the Central Zone.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In addition there were a few venues that, by necessity, were outside the boundaries of Greater London, such as the Weymouth and Portland National Sailing Academy some 125 mi (201 km) southwest of London, which hosted the sailing events.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The football tournament was staged at several grounds around the UK.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Work began on the Park in December 2006, when a sports hall in Eton Manor was pulled down.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The athletes' village in Portland was completed in September 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In November 2004 the 200-hectare (500-acre) Olympic Park plans were revealed.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The plans for the site were approved in September 2004 by Tower Hamlets, Newham, Hackney and Waltham Forest.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The redevelopment of the area to build the Olympic Park required compulsory purchase orders of property.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The London Development Agency was in dispute with London and Continental Railways about the orders in November 2005.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] By May 2006, 86% of the land had been bought as businesses fought eviction.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Residents who opposed the eviction tried to find ways to stop it by setting up campaigns, but they had to leave as 94% of land was bought and the other 6% bought as a £9 billion regeneration project started.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There were some issues with the original venues not being challenging enough or being financially unviable.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Both the Olympic road races and the mountain bike event were initially considered to be too easy, so they were eventually scheduled on new locations.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic marathon course, which was set to finish in the Olympic stadium, was moved to The Mall, since closing Tower Bridge was deemed to cause traffic problems in central London.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] North Greenwich Arena 2 was scrapped in a cost-cutting exercise, Wembley Arena being used for badminton and rhythmic gymnastics events instead.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Test events were held throughout 2011 and 2012, either through an existing championship such as 2012 Wimbledon Championships or as a specially created event held under the banner of *London Prepares*.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Team GB House was the British Olympic Association's operational HQ up to and during the 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Designed by architects Gebler Tooth on the top floor of an office building in Westfield Stratford City, it combined the team HQ, athletes' "Friends and Family" lounge, Press Centre, and VIP lounge.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] IOC's initial evaluation felt that, if transport improvements were delivered in time for the Games, London would cope.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Transport for London (TfL) carried out numerous improvements in preparation for 2012, including the expansion of the London Overground's East London Line, upgrades to the Docklands Light Railway and the North London Line, and the introduction of a new "Javelin" high-speed rail service.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] According to Network Rail, an additional 4,000 train services operated during the Games, and train operators ran longer trains during the day.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] During the Games, Stratford International station was not served by any international services (just as it had not been before the Games), westbound trains did not stop at Hackney Wick railway station, and Pudding Mill Lane DLR station closed entirely during the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] TfL also built a £25 million cable car across the River Thames, called the Emirates Air Line, to link 2012 Olympics venues.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It was inaugurated in June 2012 and crosses the Thames between Greenwich Peninsula and the Royal Docks, carrying up to 2,500 passengers an hour, cutting journey times between The O2 and the ExCeL exhibition centre and providing a crossing every 30 seconds.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The plan was to have 80% of athletes travel less than 20 minutes to their event and 93% of them within 30 minutes of their event.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic Park would be served by ten separate railway lines with a combined capacity of 240,000 passengers per hour.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In addition, LOCOG planned for 90% of the venues to be served by three or more types of public transport.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Two park-and-ride sites off the M25 with a combined capacity of 12,000 cars were 25 minutes away from the Olympic Park.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Another park-and-ride site was planned in Ebbsfleet with a capacity for 9,000 cars where spectators could board a 10-minute shuttle train service.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] To get spectators to Eton Dorney, four park-and-ride schemes were set up.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These Park and Ride services were operated by First Games Transport.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] TfL defined a network of roads leading between venues as the Olympic Route Network; roads connecting all of the Olympic venues located within London.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Many of these roads also contained special "Olympic lanes" marked with the Olympic rings—reserved for the use of Olympic athletes, officials, and other VIPs during the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Members of the public driving in an Olympic lane were subject to a fine of £130.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Additionally, London buses would not include roads with Olympic lanes on their routes.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Concerns were expressed at the logistics of spectators travelling to the events outside London.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In particular, the sailing events at Portland had no direct motorway connections, and local roads are heavily congested by tourist traffic in the summer.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] However, a £77 million relief road connecting Weymouth to Dorchester was built and opened in 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Some £16 million was put aside for the rest of the improvements.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] TfL created a promotional campaign and website, *Get Ahead of the Games*, to help provide information related to transport during the Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Through the campaign, TfL also encouraged the use of cycling as a mode of transport.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A temporary terminal was created at Heathrow Airport to be used by 10,100 departing athletes after the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Up to 35% more bags than normal were expected on 13 August, which was predicted to be the busiest day in the airport's history, according to Nick Cole, head of Olympic and Paralympic planning at Heathrow.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A study from Oxford University found that the sports-related costs of London 2012 amounted to US$15 billion, compared with $4.6 billion for Rio 2016, $40–44 billion for Beijing 2008, and $51 billion for Sochi 2014 (the most expensive Olympics in history).
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London 2012 went over budget by 76% in real terms, measured from bid to completion.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This does not include wider costs for urban and transport infrastructure, which often equal or exceed the sports-related costs.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The costs of staging the Games were separate from those for building the venues and infrastructure and redeveloping the land for the Olympic Park.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] While the Games were privately funded, the venues and infrastructure were largely financed using public money.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, the original budget for the Games was increased to about £9.3 billion (US$15.28 billion) in 2007.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The revised figures were announced to the House of Commons on 15 March 2007 by Tessa Jowell.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Unpaid volunteers known as Games Makers performed a variety of tasks before and during the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A target of 70,000 volunteers was set as early as 2004.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] When recruitment took place in 2010, more than 240,000 applications were received.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Sebastian Coe said in February 2012, "Our Games Makers will contribute a total of around eight million volunteer hours during the Games and the Games simply wouldn't happen without them".
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The volunteers wore clothing that included purple and red polo shirts and jackets, beige trousers, grey socks and grey-and-white trainers, which they collected from the Uniform Distribution and Accreditation Centre.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Volunteers also wore photo accreditation badges that were also worn by officials, athletes, family members and media, which gained them access to specific venues and buildings around the site.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Organisers estimated that some 8 million tickets would be available for the Olympic Games, and 1.5 million tickets for the Paralympic Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] LOCOG aimed to raise £375–£400 million in ticket sales.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There were also free events such as marathon, triathlon and road cycling, although, for the first time in Olympic history, the sailing events were ticketed.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Eventually, more than 7,000,000 tickets were sold.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Following IOC rules, people applied for tickets from the NOC of their country of residence.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] European Union residents were able to apply for tickets in any EU country.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In Great Britain, ticket prices ranged from £20 for many events to £2,012 for the most expensive seats at the opening ceremony.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Some free tickets were given to military personnel as part of the Tickets For Troops scheme, as well as to survivors and families of those who died during the 7 July 2005 London bombings.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Initially, people were able to apply for tickets via a website from 15 March until 26 April 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There was a huge demand for tickets, with a demand of more than three times the number of tickets available.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 11 May 2012 a round of nearly one million "second chance" tickets went on sale over a 10-day period between 23 June and 3 July 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] About 1.7 million tickets were available for football and 600,000 for other sports, including archery, field hockey, football, judo, boxing and volleyball.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Ten sports had sold out by 8 am of the first day.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] During the closing ceremony of the 2008 Olympics, the Olympic Flag was formally handed over from the Mayor of Beijing to the Mayor of London.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This was followed by a section highlighting London, One month later, the Olympic and Paralympic flags were raised outside the London City Hall.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A countdown clock in Trafalgar Square was unveiled, 500 days before the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It was a two-sided clock with the Paralympic countdown on the other side.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The countdown to the start of the Olympics began with a ceremony for the lighting of the Olympic flame in Olympia, Greece.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The police led the security operation (named **Operation Olympics** by the Ministry of Defence), with 10,000 officers available, supported by 13,500 members of the British Armed Forces.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Naval and air assets were deployed as part of the security operation, including ships situated in the Thames, Typhoon fighter jets and surface-to-air missiles; it was the biggest security operation Britain had faced in decades.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The cost of security increased from £282 million to £553 million, and the figure of 13,500 armed forces personnel was greater than the number deployed at the time in Afghanistan.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Metropolitan Police and the Royal Marines carried out security exercises in preparation for the Olympics on 19 January 2012, with 50 marine police officers in rigid inflatables and fast response boats, joined by up to 100 military personnel and a Royal Navy Lynx helicopter.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Ministry of Defence distributed leaflets to residents of the Lexington building in Bow, announcing that a missile system was to be stationed on top of the water tower.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Ministry said it probably would use Starstreak missiles and that site evaluations had taken place, but that no final decision had taken place.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Approximately 4,700 Olympic and Paralympic medals were produced by the Royal Mint at Llantrisant.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] They were designed by David Watkins (Olympics) and Lin Cheung (Paralympics).
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] 99% of the gold, silver and copper was donated by Rio Tinto from a mine in Salt Lake County, Utah in the U.S.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The remaining 1% came from a Mongolian mine.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Each medal weighs 375–400 g (13.2–14.1 oz), has a diameter of 85 mm (3.3 in) and is 7 mm (0.28 in) thick, with the sport and discipline engraved on the rim.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The medals were transferred to the Tower of London vaults on 2 July 2012 for storage.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Each gold medal is 92.5 percent silver and 1.34 percent gold, with the remainder copper.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The silver medal is 92.5 percent silver, with the remainder copper.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The bronze medal is made up of 97 percent copper, 2.5 percent zinc, and 0.5 per cent tin.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The value of the materials in the gold medal was about £410 (US$644), the silver about £210 (US$330), and the bronze about £3 (US$4.71) as of 30 July 2012.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, the same podium design was used for both the Summer Olympics and the Summer Paralympics, reflecting the organizers’ intention to establish a unified visual identity across the two events.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The royal purple podiums and ceremonial costumes used during the victory ceremonies of the 2012 Summer Olympics were designed by students from the Royal College of Art in collaboration with the London 2012 organizing committee.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The students worked on the project for approximately eight months, developing designs intended to reflect the identity and atmosphere of the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The podiums were inspired by the official emblem of the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The students used the angular design of the logo as the basis for the podium concept, extending its lines outward to create a three-dimensional structure intended to be viewed from multiple angles.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] To complement the visual identity adopted across the Olympic venues, the podiums were produced in a purple colour scheme, which organizers stated was intended to embody the energy and dynamism of the athletes competing at the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The podiums featured dynamic lines symbolizing the energy of both the Olympic Games and the athletes competing in them.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympics torch relay ran from 19 May to 27 July 2012, before the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Plans for the relay were developed in 2010–11, with the torch-bearer selection process announced on 18 May 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The torch was designed by Edward Barber and Jay Osgerby.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 18 May 2012 the Olympic flame arrived at RNAS Culdrose in Cornwall from Greece on flight BA2012, operated by a British Airways Airbus A319 named "Firefly".
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The relay lasted 70 days, with 66 evening celebrations and six island visits, and involved some 8,000 people carrying the torch about 8,000 mi (12,875 km), starting from Land's End in Cornwall.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The torch had three days outside the United Kingdom when it visited the Isle of Man on 2 June, Dublin in Ireland, on 6 June, and both Guernsey and Jersey on 15 July.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The relay focused on National Heritage Sites, locations with sporting significance, key sporting events, schools registered with the Get Set School Network, green spaces and biodiversity, Live Sites (city locations with large screens), and festivals and other events.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Dumfries and Galloway was the only Region in the whole of the United Kingdom that had the Olympic Torch pass through it twice.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A group of young athletes, nominated by retired Olympic athletes, ran the torch around the stadium.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These torchbearers were Callum Airlie, Jordan Duckitt, Desiree Henry, Katie Kirk, Cameron MacRitchie, Aidan Reynolds and Adelle Tracey.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Together the torchbearers each lit a petal that spread the fire to the 204 petals of the cauldron, representing the countries that participated in the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The cauldron was designed by Thomas Heatherwick.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic Park was planned to incorporate 45 hectares of wildlife habitat, with a total of 525 bird boxes and 150 bat boxes.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Local waterways and riverbanks were enhanced as part of the process.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Renewable energy also featured at the Olympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It was originally planned to provide 20% of the energy for the Olympic Park and Village from renewable technologies; however, only 9% of it was achieved.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Proposals to meet the original target included large-scale on-site wind turbines and hydroelectric generators in the River Thames, but these plans were scrapped for safety reasons.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The focus subsequently moved to installing solar panels on some buildings, and providing the opportunity to recover energy from waste.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Where it could not be reused or recycled, food packaging for use at the Olympics—including fast-food wrappers, sandwich boxes and drink cartons—was made from compostable materials like starch and cellulose-based bioplastics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] After use, many of these materials were suitable for anaerobic digestion (AD), allowing them to be made into renewable energy.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Post-Games, buildings like the Water Polo Arena were relocated elsewhere.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Building parts like roofing covers and membranes of different temporary venues were recycled via VinyLoop.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This allowed organisers to meet the standards of the Olympic Delivery Authority concerning environmental protection.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London 2012 inaugurated Olympic Games guidelines that included the recycling of PVC, which was used for temporary buildings such as the Basketball Arena and for the temporary parts of permanent venues such as the Olympic Stadium.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In the Water Polo Arena, PVC roofing was made from recycled cushions to provide insulation.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Basically, PVC stretched over lightweight steel frame.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This design solution makes them efficient to install, reduces the need for any significant foundations and are, of course, reusable.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] We were challenged by the public around the use of PVC; but we considered it to be the right material for certain functions.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Cultural Olympiad comprised many programmes, with more than 500 events spread over four years across the whole of the United Kingdom, and culminating in the London 2012 Festival.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Titled "The Isles of Wonder", the opening ceremony began at 21:00 British Summer Time (UTC+1) on 27 July in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Academy Award–winning director Danny Boyle was artistic director and Rick Smith of Underworld was musical director.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony was immediately seen as a tremendous success, widely praised as a "masterpiece" and "a love letter to Britain".
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The principal sections of the artistic display represented Britain's Industrial Revolution, National Health Service, literary heritage, popular music and culture, and were noted for their vibrant storytelling and use of music.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were officially opened by Queen Elizabeth II, accompanied by Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This was the second Olympic Games opened personally by the Queen, the first being in 1976 in Montreal, Canada.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The ceremony featured a short comic film starring Daniel Craig as the secret agent James Bond and the Queen as herself.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There was also a musical comedy item starring Rowan Atkinson as Mr.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Bean playing along with the London Symphony Orchestra.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These were widely ascribed to Britain's sense of humour.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Live musical performers included Frank Turner, Dame Evelyn Glennie, Mike Oldfield, Dizzee Rascal, Arctic Monkeys and Sir Paul McCartney who performed "Hey Jude" as the closing act.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Broadcast live on BBC One, the ceremony attracted a peak viewing audience of over 27 million in the UK.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The closing ceremony was held on 12 August.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It featured a flashback fiesta to British music with the Who closing the performance.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The ceremony also included a handover of the Olympic flag by Boris Johnson, Mayor of London, to Eduardo Paes, Mayor of Rio de Janeiro, the host city of the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In his closing address, Jacques Rogge described the Games as "happy and glorious".
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] During the Games, some countries and continents had a "national house".
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These temporary meeting places for supporters, athletes and other followers were located throughout London.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The 2012 Summer Olympics featured 26 different sports encompassing 40 disciplines and 302 medal events.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Women's boxing was included in the programme for the first time, and 36 women competed in three weight classes.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There was a special dispensation for the shooting events, which would otherwise have been illegal under UK gun law.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In tennis, mixed doubles returned to the Olympic programme for the first time since 1924.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London's bid featured the same 28 sports that had been included in other recent Summer Olympics, but the IOC voted to drop baseball and softball from the 2012 Games just two days after London had been selected as the host city.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There was an appeal, but the IOC voted to uphold the decision, and the two sports were scheduled to be discontinued after their last appearance at the 2008 Olympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC then voted on whether to replace them; karate, squash, golf, roller sports and rugby sevens were considered.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Karate and squash were the two final nominees, but neither received enough votes to reach the required two-thirds majority.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Although formal demonstration sports were eliminated after the 1992 Summer Olympics, special tournaments for non-Olympic sports can be run during the Games, such as the Wushu tournament at the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There were attempts to run Twenty20 cricket and netball tournaments alongside the 2012 Games, but neither campaign was successful.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The final official schedule was released on 15 February 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These Olympic Games resulted in 32 world records in eight sports.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The largest number of records were set in swimming, at eight.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] China, Great Britain and the United States set the most records, with five each.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 85 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) won medals, 54 of those countries winning at least one gold medal.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Seven NOCs won their first ever Olympic medal: Bahrain (gold), Botswana (silver), Cyprus (silver), Gabon (silver), Grenada (gold), Guatemala (silver), and Montenegro (silver).
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The United States finished at the top of the table, winning 48 gold medals and a total of 104 medals.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The host broadcaster was Olympic Broadcasting Services (OBS), an agency of the IOC.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The OBS used its own cameras and crews subcontracted from other Olympic broadcasters to cover the events.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The base video and audio were sold to other broadcasters, who added their own commentary and presentation.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The official recording format of the 2012 Summer Olympics used Panasonic's digital technologies.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The official video was produced and distributed from the International Broadcast Centre in 1080/50i High-Definition (HD) format.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Panasonic announced that DVCPRO HD would be the official recording format.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] OBS London used P2 HD shoulder-mount camcorders.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The IOC wanted television coverage to reach as broad a worldwide audience as possible, and several national and regional broadcasters covered London 2012.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In the UK, the BBC carried the Olympics and Channel 4 the Paralympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The BBC aimed to broadcast all 5,000 hours of the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] BBC Parliament's Freeview channel was suspended, BBC Three's on-air time was extended so that it could show Olympic events in the daytime, and 24 additional BBC Olympics channels were available via cable, satellite and the internet in the UK.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The US television rights, owned by NBC, accounted for more than half the rights revenue for the IOC.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Despite high viewership, many viewers were disappointed with NBC's coverage.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The operations of broadcasters granted rights to the Games were hosted in the dedicated International Broadcast Centre inside the security cordon of the Olympic Park.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] YouTube planned to stream the Games in 64 territories in Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa where there were no official broadcasters.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In Sri Lanka a dispute occurred between Sri Lanka Rupavahini Corporation (SLRC) and MBC Networks (MTV/MBC) as to who was the official broadcaster of the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] This problem was caused as Asia-Pacific Broadcasting Union (ABU) had offered the official broadcasting rights to both networks, as both of the networks were ABU members.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] So SLRC filed a case against MBC Networks for broadcasting rights at the Colombo Magistrate's Court.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Considering the case, the court issued a special court order preventing MBC Networks' Olympic broadcast and stated that SLRC should be the sole broadcaster.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] However, when the Games started, both networks broadcast most of the events simultaneously.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Another dispute had previously occurred between Carlton Sports Network (CSN) and SLRC, but the Sports Minister, Mahindananda Aluthgamage, had stated that SLRC had the exclusive rights.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In November 2012 the IOC announced the winners of the Golden Ring Awards for the best broadcast coverage of the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Best Olympic Sports Production was awarded to the sailing, produced by Christopher Lincoln, Gary Milkis, and Ursula Romero.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The production for the canoe/kayak slalom and the rowing/canoe sprint came second and third respectively.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The award for Best On Air Promotion went to NBC with Foxtel and ZDF finishing second and third.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] NBC Olympics also won the Best Olympic Feature category, as Sky Italia came second and ZDF third.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The Best Athlete Profile award went to TV Record's profile of Sarah Menezes, NBC came second with their profile of David Rudisha, and ESPN Latin America took third place with a profile of Miguel Correa and Ruben Rezola.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The award for Best Olympic Programme went to NBC, host broadcasters the BBC took second place for Super Saturday (the middle Saturday of the Games), and third place was claimed by the Nine Network for their live coverage of Day 16 of the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] "Survival" by Muse was announced as the official song of the Olympics, to be played by international broadcasters reporting on the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The track was noted to express a sense of conviction and determination to win.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In August 2009 Royal Mail commissioned artists and illustrators to design 30 stamps, which were released in batches of 10 between 2009 and 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The last ones were released on 22 July 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Two £5 coins designed by Saiman Miah were made to commemorate the Olympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] As with other Olympics since 1952, the Royal Mint struck a set of commemorative one-kilogram gold and silver coins.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The official motto for the 2012 Summer Olympics was "Inspire a generation".
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] It was chosen to highlight the organisers' commitment to inspire the world, including younger generations, to get involved in sporting events through the Games' legacy.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] A secondary motto of "Be part of it" was also used throughout marketing.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] There were two London 2012 logos: one used for the bidding process, and the other used in the branding for the Games themselves.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The bid logo, created by Kino Design, was a ribbon with blue, yellow, black, green, and red stripes winding through the text "LONDON 2012", making the shape of the River Thames in East London.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The main logo, designed by Wolff Olins and published on 4 June 2007, is a representation of the number 2012, with the Olympic Rings embedded within the zero.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Public reaction to the main logo in a June 2007 BBC poll was negative; more than 80% of votes gave it the lowest possible rating.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Several newspapers ran their own logo competitions, displaying alternative submissions from their readers, and several writers from news agencies criticised the logo.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] It was suggested that the logo resembled the American cartoon characters Lisa Simpson and Bart Simpson performing fellatio.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In February 2011 Iran threatened to boycott the Olympics, complaining that the logo appeared to spell out the word "Zion".
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The four main colours used in the branding of the Games were pink, blue, green and orange.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] These colours were chosen to showcase the spirit of the Games: energetic, spirited, youthful, and bright.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The auxiliary colours used in the branding were dark purple, grey, and gold.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] These were mostly used in symbols and graphics to offset the brightness of the main colours.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The official mascots for the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympic Games were unveiled on 19 May 2010.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Wenlock and Mandeville are animations depicting two drops of steel from a steelworks in Bolton.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] They are named after Much Wenlock, a town in Shropshire that holds a forerunner of the current Olympic Games, and Stoke Mandeville, a village in Buckinghamshire where a forerunner of the Paralympic Games was first held.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The writer Michael Morpurgo wrote the story concept for the mascots, and an animation was produced.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Four stories have been created about the mascots: *Out Of A Rainbow*, *Adventures On A Rainbow*, *Rainbow Rescue*, and *Rainbow to the Games*.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The 1981 Academy Award for Best Picture–winning film *Chariots of Fire*, which tells the story of two British athletes in the 1924 Olympics, was a recurring theme in promotions for the 2012 Olympics.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] A digitally re-mastered version of *Chariots of Fire* was released on 13 July 2012 and screened in over 100 UK cinemas as part of the celebrations, and a stage adaptation ran in London theatres from 9 May 2012 to 5 January 2013.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The film's theme tune was performed during the opening ceremony by the London Symphony Orchestra, conducted by Simon Rattle.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The performance was accompanied by a comedic skit by Rowan Atkinson, which included the opening beach-running footage from the film.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] A new orchestration of the film's theme tune was played during each medal presentation of the Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] During the lead-up to the Games, there were controversies over sponsorship, the athletes' use of social media, and several political issues.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] After a complicated lottery process, thousands of people failed to secure seats for the events they wanted, but a large number of empty seats were observed early in the Games, even at some of the most popular events.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] There was speculation that this was due to a failure of corporate sponsors to make use of tickets they had received.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] During the Games, eight competitors in the badminton women's doubles were disqualified for "not using best efforts", when they tried to lose matches in the group stage to obtain more favourable fixtures in the knockout rounds.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] A number of results in boxing, gymnastics and judo were overturned by officials after initial decisions were appealed against.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] It was announced before the Summer Games that half of all the competitors would be tested for drugs, with 150 scientists set to take 6,000 samples between the start of the Games and the end of the Paralympic Games.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Every competitor who won a medal was also tested.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympic laboratory tested up to 400 samples every day for more than 240 prohibited substances.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Although there were less than 10 doping violations detected during the games, in the years following many samples were retested with improved laboratory procedures.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] This resulted in a large number of disqualifications and rescinded medals.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] As of mid 2024, 44 medals have been stripped due to doping violations with around 130 total disqualifications.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In particular, almost 50 were from Russian athletes.
[src:south-sudan/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Testing for drugs was completed by GSK (GlaxoSmithKline).
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The **South Sudanese Civil War** was a multi-sided civil war in South Sudan fought from 2013 to 2018 between government and opposition forces.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The civil war caused rampant human rights abuses, including forced displacement, ethnic massacres, and killings of journalists by various parties.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Since the war's end, South Sudan has been governed by a coalition formed by leaders of the former warring factions, Salva Kiir Mayardit and Riek Machar.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The country continues to recover from the war while experiencing ongoing and systemic ethnic violence.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In December 2013, President Kiir accused his former deputy Machar and 10 others of attempting a coup d'état.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Machar denied trying to start a coup and fled to lead the Sudan People's Liberation Movement-in-Opposition (SPLM-IO).
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Fighting broke out between the Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) and SPLM-IO, igniting the civil war.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Ugandan troops were deployed to fight alongside the South Sudanese government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The United Nations has peacekeepers in the country as part of the United Nations Mission in South Sudan (UNMISS).
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In January 2014, the first ceasefire agreement was reached.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Fighting continued and was followed by several more ceasefire agreements.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Negotiations were mediated by IGAD, the African Union, the United Nations, China, the European Union, the United States, the United Kingdom and Norway; the "Compromise Peace Agreement" was signed in August 2015.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Machar returned to Juba in 2016 and was appointed vice president.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Following a second breakout of fighting within Juba, the SPLM-IO fled to the surrounding and previously peaceful Equatoria region.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Kiir replaced Machar as First Vice President with Taban Deng Gai, splitting the opposition, and rebel in-fighting became a major part of the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] A rivalry between the President and the former army chief Paul Malong Awan also led to fighting.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In August 2018, a ceasefire came into effect, and on 12 September 2018 the war officially ended with the signing of the Revitalized Agreement on the Resolution of the Conflict in the Republic of South Sudan (R-ARCSS).
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] On 22 February 2020, rivals Kiir and Machar struck a unity deal and formed a coalition government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] By April 2018, it was estimated that about 400,000 people, 10.6% of which were children, had been killed in the war.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] This death toll includes notable atrocities, such as the 2013 Nuer massacre and the 2014 Bentiu massacre.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Although both parties otherwise had supporters from across South Sudan's ethnic divides, there were strong tensions between the Dinka and Nuer, which were often violent.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Kiir's Dinka ethnic group has been accused of attacking other ethnic groups and Machar's Nuer ethnic group has been accused of attacking the Dinka.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] More than 4 million people have been displaced, with about 1.8 million of those internally displaced, and about 2.5 million having fled to neighboring countries, especially Uganda and Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Fighting in the agricultural heartland in the south of the country caused the number of people facing starvation to soar to 6 million, leading to the 2017 famine.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The country's economy has also been devastated.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In October 2017, the IMF reported that real income had halved since 2013 and inflation was more than 300% per annum.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The Comprehensive Peace Agreement signed on 9 January 2005 between the Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) and the Government of Sudan ended the Second Sudanese Civil War, which had started in 1983.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Under the terms of the peace agreement, a Southern Sudan Autonomous Region was created and run by the SPLM with a promise that a referendum on independence would be held in 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] During the six years period of autonomy, the desire for independence kept in-fighting within the SPLM in check.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] One consequence of the war's end was the oil fields in southern Sudan could be developed far more extensively than was possible during the war.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Between 2006 and 2009, sales of oil brought in an annual average of US$2.1 billion to the Southern Sudan Autonomous Region.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Disputes between leading personalities in the SPLM over how to appropriate the oil revenue led to recurring tensions.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] A system emerged during the autonomous period where SPLM leaders used the wealth generated by the oil to buy the loyalty of not only the troops, but the people at large, creating intense competition to control the oil.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In 2010, after a disputed election, George Athor led the South Sudan Democratic Movement in rebellion against the government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The same year, a faction of the South Sudan Democratic Movement, called the Cobra Faction, led by David Yau Yau rebelled against the government, accusing them of being prejudiced against the Murle.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] His faction signed a cease-fire with the government in 2011 and his militia was reintegrated into the army but he defected again in 2012.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] After the army's 2010 disarmament campaign which saw widespread abuses against the Shilluk people, John Uliny of the Shilluk people began a rebellion, leading the Upper Nile faction of the South Sudan Democratic Movement.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Gabriel Tang, who led a militia allied to Khartoum during the Second Sudanese Civil War, clashed regularly with the SPLA until 2011 when his soldiers were reintegrated into the national army.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In 2011, Peter Gadet led a rebellion with the South Sudan Liberation Army, but was reintegrated into the army the same year.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Former rebellious militias were recruited into the South Sudan Liberation Army, a policy which has been described as "bad culture" and an incentive to rebel.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] During the 2011 referendum 98% of voters voted in favour of independence, with South Sudan becoming an independent state on 9 July 2011.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] After rumors about a planned coup surfaced in Juba in late 2012, South Sudanese President Salva Kiir began to reorganize the senior leadership of his government, party, and military at an unprecedented scale.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In January 2013, Kiir replaced the inspector general of the national police service with a lieutenant from the army and dismissed six deputy chiefs of staff and 29 major generals in the army.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In February 2013, Kiir retired an additional 117 army generals with the move being regarded as a power grab by some.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Kiir suggested that his rivals were trying to revive the rifts that had provoked infighting in the 1990s.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] In July 2013, Kiir dismissed Vice President Riek Machar, one-time leader of the Nasir revolt, along with his entire cabinet.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Kiir suspended the SPLM Secretary-General Pagan Amum Okech and forbade him from leaving Juba or speaking to the media.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The decrees elicited fears of political unrest, with Machar claiming that Kiir's move was a step towards dictatorship and announcing that he would challenge Kiir in the 2015 presidential election.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] He said that if the country is to be united, it cannot tolerate "one man's rule." In November 2013 Kiir disbanded all of the top-level organs of the SPLM party, including the Political Bureau, the National Convention and the National Liberation Council.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] He cited their failed performance and the expiration of their term limits.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] For millennia, human society in the South Sudan region operated as a barter economy, with cattle being the primary medium of exchange.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Cattle raids between different ethnic groups were an accepted and honorable way to acquire more cattle.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] However, there were widely accepted limits on the amount of violence permissible in cattle raids, and tribal elders would intervene if cattle raid violence became excessive.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Furthermore, the antiquated weapons used in cattle raids were not likely to inflict mass casualties.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] This policy failed to end the rebellion, but it did cause the breakdown of accepted norms regarding violence on cattle raids and an increase in ethnic tensions between the peoples of southern Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] The Nuer White Army released a statement stating its intention to "wipe out the entire Murle tribe on the face of the earth as the only solution to guarantee long-term security of Nuer's cattle".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Notably, in the Pibor massacre, between 900 and 3,000 people were killed in Pibor.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Although Machar and Kiir are both members of the SPLM, they stem from different tribes with a history of conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p01] Kiir is an ethnic Dinka, while Machar is an ethnic Nuer.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 15 December 2013, opposition leaders Dr.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Riek Machar, Pagan Amum and Rebecca Nyandeng voted to boycott the National Liberation Council meeting in the Nyakuron neighbourhood of Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The *Sudan Tribune* reported clashes breaking out on 15 December in the Munuki neighbourhood of Juba between members of the presidential guard.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Kiir also claimed that the fighting began when unidentified, uniformed personnel started shooting at a meeting of the SPLM.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The military headquarters near Juba University was then attacked, with occasional fighting continuing to the next day.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Heavy gunfire and mortar fire were reported on 16 December, and UNMISS announced that hundreds of civilians sought refuge inside its facilities.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Military spokesman, Philip Aguer said that some military installations had been attacked but that "the army is in full control of Juba," that the situation was unlikely to deescalate, and that an investigation was under way.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Several people were also injured during the fighting.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Juba International Airport was closed indefinitely; Kenyan airlines Fly540 and Kenya Airways indefinitely suspended flights to Juba after the airport closed.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] A dusk-to-dawn curfew was imposed until further notice.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] State-owned SSTV went off-air for several hours.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] When it returned to broadcasting, it aired a message by President Salva Kiir.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The dissident group was said to include Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) founder John Garang's widow, Rebecca Garang.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Former Minister of Higher Education Peter Adwok Nyaba said that on the evening 15 December after the meeting of the National Liberation Council had failed, Kiir told Major General Marial Ciennoung to disarm his soldiers of the "Tiger Battalion," which he did.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Adwok then controversially claimed that the officer in charge of the weapons stores, opened them and rearmed only the Dinka soldiers.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] A Nuer soldier questioned this and a fistfight ensued which lead to more soldiers getting involved and raiding the stores and culminated in the Nuer soldiers taking control of the military headquarters.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The next morning, Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) reinforcements arrived and dislodged the mutineers.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] He was later detained at the Juba airport when attempting to leave the country.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Other arrests included those of Kiir's critics.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Information Minister Micheal Makuei Leuth claimed that Machar had left Juba with some soldiers and stolen cattle.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 21 December, the government announced its unconditional readiness to hold peace talks with any rebel group, including Machar In a Christmas message, Kiir warned of the fighting becoming a tribal conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Chief Whip and MP from Eastern Equatoria, Tulio Odongi Ayahu, announced his support for Kiir.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Machar spoke for the first time since the crisis began on 18 December in which he said he was not aware of any coup attempt, but instead blamed Kiir for fabricating the coup in order to settle political scores and target political opponents.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] He accused Kiir of inciting ethnic tensions to achieve his ends.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] He also said the violence was started by the presidential guard, which was founded by Kiir and told to report directly to him instead of the military.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] He refused to deny or acknowledge support for Gadet but that "the rebels are acting in the right direction." On 22 December, Machar said he wanted to be the leader of the country and that "his" forces would maintain control of the country's oil fields.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The local *Radio Tamazuj* suggested UNMISS were absent from the streets in Juba and that president of the UN Security Council Gérard Araud, had announced that the peacekeepers would not intervene in the fighting.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Human Rights Watch described an incident during the Juba conflict in which 200–300 Nuer men were collected, place in a room and then shot at, killing most of the men.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The next day, witnesses reported seeing around 200 bodies being moved from a clinic in the Jebel area of Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] A semblance of calm returned to Juba by 18 December, though there were unconfirmed reports of several students being killed by security personnel at Juba University.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The UN announced that thousands of people had sought refuge within its compounds with 13,000 people taking refuge in its two compounds in Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Two Indian peacekeepers were killed on 19 December whilst helping to protect 36 civilians in Akobo, Jonglei, when they were attacked by about 2,000 armed Nuer youths.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The attack was condemned by the UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 10 February 2014, one of the UN compounds in Juba was surrounded by armed government troops and policemen, who demanded that the UN surrender the Nuer civilians sheltering there.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] About 200 employees of petroleum operators, of which the three largest were China National Petroleum Corp, ONGC Videsh and Petronas, sought refuge at an UN compound in Bentiu.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] This followed the deaths of 16 such workers: five workers at a field in Unity State on 18 December and the other 11 at the Thar Jath field the next day.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Government soldiers then took control of the fields and said that production continued normally.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The rebels had reportedly taken over at least some of the country's oil fields amidst fears of Sudan intervening in the country.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Pariang county in northern Unity is home to the Rueng Dinka—the only Dinka group in the state.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Fighting broke out in Pariang on 20 December, when some SPLA troops defected to the rebels.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 24 December, an estimated 400 defectors moved southwards from Jaw, the SPLA's northernmost operating base, towards positions held by SPLA forces loyal to Koang Chuol.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By 26 December, the SPLA claimed to have destroyed 37 rebel vehicles in Pariang county, which remained under their control.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Following calls from the Government of South Sudan, Uganda deployed its troops to Juba to assist in securing the airport and evacuating Ugandan citizens.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 21 December a flight of three US Air Force V-22 Osprey aircraft en route to evacuate US nationals from Bor took small arms fire from the ground, injuring four Navy SEALs.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] South Sudan blamed the rebels for the incident.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] A second evacuation attempt by four UN and civilian helicopters succeeded in evacuating about 15 US nationals, Sudanese-Americans and those working in humanitarian operations, from the United Nations base in Bor on 22 December.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Although the base was surrounded by 2,000 armed youths, a rebel commander had promised safe passage for the evacuation.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In total 380 officials and private citizens as well as about 300 foreign citizens were flown to Nairobi.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The United States military announced a repositioning of its forces in Africa to prepare for possible further evacuations as the United Nations warned of the planned strikes.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Many of these reports have come from the hundreds of foreign oil company employees gathered at the airport to leave.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Five Ugandan and ten Kenyan citizens were also evacuated from Bor and Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The Kenyan government said that there were 30,000 of its nationals in the country and that 10,000 had applied for emergency documents.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 22 December 2013, U.S. and Nigerian envoys were on their way to Juba to try to negotiate a solution.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The U.S. envoy to the country, Donald Booth, said that having spoken to Kiir, the latter was committed to talks with Machar without preconditions.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Machar said that the rebel side was ready for talks that could possibly occur in Ethiopia.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] He said he wanted free and fair elections and that it is best if Kiir leaves.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] His conditions for talks were that his "comrades", including Rebecca Garang and Pagan Amum, be released from detention to be evacuated to Addis Ababa.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Information minister Makuei said those involved in the coup would not be released and dismissed claims that the rebels had taken the major oil fields.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Fighting had spread to Bor by 17 December, where three people had died and over 1,000 people sought refuge in the UN base.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The situation escalated when around 2,000 soldiers led by Peter Gadet revolted and attacked the city of Bor on 18 December.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The rebels quickly seized much of the settlement.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Ethnically targeted violence was also reported and the Dinka feared a repeat of the Bor massacre.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 23 December, Aguer said the army was on its way to Jonglei and Unity to retake territory.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 24 December, The Government of South Sudan claimed to have recaptured Bor despite fighting still taking place in parts of the town.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Most of Gadet and most of his forces had withdrawn.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 27 December, Machar condemned Ugandan interference and claimed Ugandan air forces bombed their positions in Bor.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] There was also tension at the UN compound in the city as armed fighters had entered it and about 17,000 civilians seeking protection were at the location.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The UN also reported that their base was being reinforced with additional protective barriers, including the area hosting the displaced civilians.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 29 December, a UN helicopter spotted a group of armed youths 50 kilometres (31 miles) from Bor but could not confirm their numbers.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 30 December, South Sudanese government troops clashed with Nuer White Army militiamen and other rebel factions loyal to Machar near Bor.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By 31 December, the rebels were close to reaching the center of Bor and by 2 January, Mayor of Bor, Nhial Majak Nhial said that the government had withdrawn from the city and Kiir declared a state of emergency in Unity and Jonglei states, where rebels controlled the capitals.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 4 January intense battles involving tanks and artillery were reported on the outskirts of Bor, which by this time had changed hands three times since fighting began.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Rebels claimed that a South Sudanese army general has been killed in the fighting, as his convoy approaching Bor was ambushed.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The SPLA brought large numbers of reinforcements bringing the total SPLA troops 25 km (16 mi) from Bor close to 2,000.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 24 December, fighting was reported in Malakal, with Sudanese presidential spokesperson Ateny Wek Ateny claiming that the Upper Nile oil fields were far from Malakal and secure.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 27 December, the army said it had taken back full control of Malakal, the administrative center of Upper Nile, a state which supplied all of South Sudan's crude oil, after fighting shut down oil fields in other areas.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By February 2014, the UN compound in Malakal housed around 20,000 people who had fled the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The UNMISS reported that on 14 January heavy fighting broke out near the UN compound in Malakal with one civilian killed and dozens wounded during the battle.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Civilians emptied out of the town, and at least 200 drowned when their overcrowded boat sank as they tried to flee across the Nile.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 15 January, fighting continued in the streets of Malakal with both sides claiming to control the town.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 18 February 2014, fighting between members of various ethnicities broke out within the UN Mission in the capital city of Upper Nile State, Malakal, resulting in ten deaths.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 20 December commander of the SPLA 4th Division, James Koang, declared himself military governor of Unity State, his forces then clashed with those loyal to Kiir resulting in the forces loyal to Kiir retreating to the barraks in Bentiu.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The next day, Koang announced allegiance to Machar and declared an 'interim government' of the state with state governor Joseph Nguen Monytuel fleeing Mayom county.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The soldiers loyal to Kiir retreated to Abiemnom County and were reinforced by Western Bahr el Ghazal's 5th division and the Northern Bahr el Ghazal's 3rd division to take back Bentiu.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] South Sudan Liberation Movement (SSLA) militia forces, led by the Bul Nuer commander Matthew Puljang, decided to support them.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By 27 December, a combined force of SSLA and SPLA seized Mayom, 90 kilometers from Bentiu, on 29 December.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Peter Dak, the rebel commander in Mayom, announced that he fled the town on 7 January.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Around 8 January 2014, the SPLA forces advanced on Bentiu, which had been mostly evacuated, securing the city on 10 January 2014.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In January 2014, direct negotiations between both sides, as mediated by IGAD, the African Union the United Nations, China, the EU, the US, the UK and Norway, began.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] South Sudanese troops retook Bor on 18 January and Malakal on 20 January.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Government troops were assisted by Ugandan troops, against the wishes of IGAD who feared a wider regional conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Uganda announced they had joined the conflict in support of Kiir in January after previously denying it, having said the troops were only there to evacuate Ugandan nationals.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 23 January 2014, representatives of the Government of South Sudan and representatives of Riek Machar reached a ceasefire agreement in Ethiopia.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Three days later both sides accused each other of breaking the ceasefire agreement.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The rebels accused the government of attacking the town of Leer and other rebel held positions and that the attacks were an attempt to sabotage the second round of talks scheduled for later in February.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The rebels threatened to boycott the second round talks, demanding the release of four remaining political prisoners and the withdrawal of Ugandan forces.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On February 18, the rebels attacked the strategic government-controlled town of Malakal and later captured it.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The government claimed to have recaptured the town on the 20 March, with the rebels claiming that they had only withdrawn to the southern portion of the town.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In April, rebels claimed once again to have seized Bentiu and by 19 April South Sudan's army admitted to have "lost communication" with commanders battling in Unity state.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The 2014 Bentiu massacre occurred on 15 April in Bentiu when more than 400 civilians were killed mostly along ethnic lines after rebels took control of the town.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Machar claimed his forces were not responsible.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] A mosque, hospital, and church were targeted where civilians had sought refuge from the fighting.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] After the fall of Bentiu, Salva Kiir replaced army chief James Hoth Mai with Paul Malong Awan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In May 2014, the government signed a peace agreement with the Murle-dominated Cobra Faction of the South Sudan Democratic Movement, led by David Yau Yau.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] As part of the agreement, a semi-autonomous area called the Greater Pibor Administrative Area was created to increase the minority populations within its borders and David Yau Yau was appointed chief administrator, equivalent to state governor.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In February 2015, a largely Murle group, unhappy with the agreement with the government, split off from the Cobra Faction to form the Greater Pibor Forces and declared allegiance to Machar.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] One of their disagreements with the government was the alleged provoking of the Murle to fight against anti-government Nuer groups in Jonglei.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In April 2016, Murle fighters in South Sudan crossed over to Gambela in Ethiopia and killed more than 200 people, stole 2,000 cattle and kidnapped more than 100 children from the Nuer tribe.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 9 May 2014, President Salva Kiir and Riek Machar signed a second ceasefire agreement in Addis Ababa.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Hostilities were to end in 24 hours and humanitarian corridors were to be opened while a permanent ceasefire was worked on.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Hours after the ceasefire was to come into effect, both sides accused each other of violating the ceasefire.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 11 June 2014, both parties agreed to begin talks on the formation of a transitional government within 60 days and to a third ceasefire.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] However, the talks collapsed as both sides boycotted them, and by 16 June, the ceasefire was reported to have been violated.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In August 2014, Kiir and leaders of South Sudan's neighbouring states signed a roadmap for the creation of a transitional government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Machar refused to sign, accusing the leaders of IGAD, of tilting the process in favour of Kiir.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In November 2014, renewed the ceasefire agreement with IGAD mediators giving them 15 days to make a power-sharing deal and threatening sanctions if they do not.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] This ceasefire down 24 hours later with fighting in the north.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In January 2015, rival factions of the SPLM signed a reunification agreement in Arusha, Tanzania, but fighting continued.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In February 2015, Kiir and Machar signed a document on "Areas of Agreement" to work towards the establishment of a transitional government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The talks later collapsed and fighting broke out in March.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Arms dealers sold weapons to both sides.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] A series of networks emerged to sell weapons with the principal sources of arms being Egypt, Uganda, Ukraine, Israel and China.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In July 2014, the Chinese arms manufacturer Norinco delivered a shipment of 95,000 assault rifles and 20 million rounds of ammunition to the government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The government asked Norinco if with was possible for them to set up a factory in South Sudan, with Norinco declining.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] American arms dealer, Erik Prince, sold three Russian-made Mi-24 attack helicopters and two L-39 jets to the government for US$43 million.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The aircraft were flown by Hungarian mercenaries with one of the mercenaries, Tibor Czingali, posting photographs on his Facebook account of bullet holes in his jet.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In Spain, police arrested Franco-Polish arms dealer, Pierre Dadak, at his luxury villa in Ibiza.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Documents found at the villa showed that Dadak had a contract with the rebels to sell them 40,000 AK-47 assault rifles, 30,000 PKM machine guns and 200,000 boxes of ammunition.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In July 2014, the government's National Security Service signed a contract worth US$264 million with a Seychelles-based shell company to buy 50,000 AK-47s, 20 million bullets and 30 tanks.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The demand for weapons had a disastrous impact on the elephant population as the rebels kill elephants to sell their tusks on the black market to earn money to buy arms.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The number of known elephants in South Sudan declined from 2,300 in 2013 to 730 in 2016.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] John Uliny, leader of a government-aligned militia had his forces switched sides to oppose the government after Kiir announced plans to replace South Sudan's 10 states with 28 states, a move which Uliny viewed as taking land from the Shilluk.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 16 May 2015, Uliny's militia and elements of the SPLM-IO captured Upper Nile's capital, Malakal, as well as Anakdiar and areas around Kodok.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] His Shilluk militia group now called itself the 'Agwelek forces'.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The group said they want to run their affairs independently from others in Upper Nile State, and the SPLM-IO backed away from claims that it was in charge of Uliny's group and stated that Uliny's interests simply coincides with theirs.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The SPLM-IO said they understood that the Shilluk community wanted a level of independence and that was why they created Fashoda State and appointed Tijwog Aguet, a Shilluk, as governor.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Gatkuoth stated he wishes for a president who was neither Dinka nor Nuer and intended to register his group as a political group called the "Federal Democratic Party" and that their forces would be called the "South Sudan National Army".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In late August 2015, Salva Kiir signed a peace agreement previously signed by Riek Machar called the "Compromise Peace Agreement" mediated by IGAD and other mediators.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The agreement would restore Riek Machar as vice-president.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The agreement established the Joint Monitoring and Evaluation Commission (JMEC) responsible for monitoring and overseeing implementation of the agreement.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 20 October 2015, Uganda announced that it would voluntarily withdraw its soldiers from South Sudan, in accordance to that peace agreement.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In January 2016, David Yau Yau dissolved the Cobra Faction of the South Sudan Democratic Movement and joined the SPLM.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In January Gathoth Gatkuoth joined with the government but was dismissed by his Federal Democratic Party for doing so.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In April 2016, as part of the peace deal, Machar returned to Juba with troops loyal to him and was sworn in as vice-president.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On Christmas Eve 2015, Salva Kiir announced he was going forward with a plan to increase the number of states from 10 to 28 and then, five days later appointed new governors who were considered loyal to him.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The new borders give Kiir's Dinkas a majority in strategic locations.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Some observers felt that the government was holding on to the peace deal to maintain international aid while backing campaigns to increase Dinka control over land and resources traditionally held by other groups.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] As the predominantly Shilluk Agwelek forces joined, in July 2016, with the SPLM-IO, which entered the peace agreement with the government, some Shilluk felt dissatisfied.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The predominantly Shilluk Tiger Faction New Forces formed in October 2015 and were led by General Yohanis Okiech.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] They rejected joining the SPLM-IO or the peace agreement and called for the restoration of the original 1956 borders of the Shilluk territories.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By this point, the Dinka militia leaders loyal to Kiir had grown rich by confiscating cattle (still the main currency unit in rural areas) from the Nuer, giving them a vested interest in keeping the Nuer down.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In South Sudan, ownership of cattle is closely tied to a sense of masculinity and a man who does not own cattle is not only poor, but also felt to lack manliness.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] This loss of cattle led Nuer men, to join rebel groups.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Furthermore, many of the Dinka leaders, now flushed with cattle, began to push into the province of Equatoria to seize the rich farmland for their cattle herds, causing the local farmers to fight back.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Notably, the war ceased to be an ethnic struggle, instead becoming a clan conflict with Dinka and Nuer clans professing loyalty to Kiir and Dinka and Nuer clans professing loyalty to Machar.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] One clan leader who raised a militia, James Koach, who was nominally loyal to Machar told Martell in 2016: "I don't care what deal they sign in Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The deals are with the government and where is the government?
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] They mean nothing to us and make no difference here.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] They took our wives and killed our children.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] My family's gone, so what do I care if I live or die?
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] You who come from outside don't know what that means.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Our cows are everything, because without them how do we survive?
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] They are trying to wipe us out, to remove us from the earth".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] When Dinka cattle herders, allegedly backed by the SPLA, occupied farmland, Azande youth rose up into militias mostly with the Arrow Boys, whose leader Alfred Karaba Futiyo Onyang declared allegiance to SPLM-IO and claimed to have occupied parts of Western Equatoria.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In February 2016, Dinka SPLA soldiers attacked a UN camp targeting Nuer and Shilluk who accused the government of annexing parts of their ancestral land.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] About a year after the peace agreement was signed, groups of Dinka youth and the SPLA targeted members of the Fertit in Wau, killing dozens and forcing more than 120,000 to flee their homes.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] As result, local Fertit tribal militias and groups allied with the SPLM-IO rose in rebellion, causing heavy clashes in the formerly relatively peaceful Wau State, which continued for months.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Violence erupted in July 2016 after an attack outside of where President Kiir and Riek Machar were meeting in Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Over 300 people were killed and over 40 people were injured, including civilians.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In the following week, 26,000 fled to neighboring Uganda.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The Indian Air Force evacuated Indian citizens from the country under Operation Sankat Mochan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] A spokesman for Riek Machar announced that South Sudan was "back to war" and that opposition forces based in areas of Juba had been attacked by forces loyal to the President.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Helicopters and tanks were reported in several parts of Juba on 10 July.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Gun battles broke out near the airport and a UN base forced the airport to close for safety reasons.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Kiir and Machar ordered a ceasefire after days of intense violence.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] After a 48-hour ultimatum given by Kiir for Machar to return to Juba to progress with the peace agreement talks passed, the SPLA-IO in Juba appointed lead negotiator Taban Deng Gai to replace Machar and the government accepted him as acting vice-president.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Machar said any talks would be illegal because Machar had previously fired Gai.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Machar, with assistance from the UN, went into exile, first to Kinshasa then to Sudan and then to South Africa, where he was allegedly kept under house arrest.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] After Machar's flight, Kiir sent his soldiers to rob the Central Bank of South Sudan, and put up $5 million US dollars stored in the central bank's vaults as a reward to anyone who could kill Machar.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Kiir's spokesman admitted to what had been done, claiming it was justified under the circumstances.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In September 2016, Machar called for armed struggle against Kiir and in November, he said SPLM-IO would not participate in a workshop organized by the JMEC, saying that the peace agreement needed to be revised.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In September, Lam Akol, leader of the largest opposition party, Democratic Change, announced a new faction called the National Democratic Movement (NDM) to overthrow Kiir.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Yohanis Okiech, who led the largely Shilluk Tiger Faction New Forces, which split from Uliny's Agwelek forces, joined the predominantly Shilluk NDM as deputy chief of general staff.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In the same month, the Cobra Faction of the South Sudan Democratic Movement, now led by Khalid Boutros declared war against the government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In August 2016, the UN Security Council authorized such a force for Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The government initially opposed the move, claiming a violation of sovereignty.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] With a resolution threatening an arms embargo if it blocked the new deployment, the government accepted the move with conditions such as the troops not being from neighboring countries, claiming they have interests at stake.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] They also accepted a hybrid court to investigate war crimes.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The US pushed for an arms embargo and sanctions on Machar and army chief Paul Malong Awan through the Security Council, but it failed to pass in December 2016.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 30 April 2017, the first batch of the Regional Protection Force arrived under Brigadier General Jean Mupenzi of Rwanda with the first phase of troops arriving in August.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Among regional powers, Kiir met, in January 2017, with Egyptian president Abdel Fattah el-Sisi who also met with Kiir's ally Ugandan President Museveni.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Egypt had previously rejected the Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam that Egypt said would diminish its share of the Nile river and Ethiopian Prime Minister, Hailemariam Desalegn had accused Egyptian institutions of supporting terrorist groups in Ethiopia.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The SPLM-IO alleged that a "dirty deal" was struck between Kiir and Egypt against Ethiopia while Kiir denied any diplomatic row.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The SPLM-IO accused the Egyptian Air Force of bombing their positions on 4 February 2017 while Egypt denied it.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] As a result of Sudan's effective counterinsurgency strategy in the War in Darfur, the biggest rebel faction, the Justice and Equality Movement (JEM), retreated to South Sudan and became involved in mercenary and criminal activities.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The SPLM-IO accused JEM as well as another rebel group in Sudan, the SPLM-North of joining the conflict on the side of Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Since the July clashes, the fighting spread from the Greater Upper Nile to include the previously safe haven of Equatoria, where the bulk of the SPLM-IO forces went for shelter from the clashes in Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] As Equatoria is the agricultural belt of the country, the number of people facing starvation soared to 6 million.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In November 2016, SPLM-IO claimed to have taken of the towns Bazi, Morobo and Kaljak.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] While the rebels were mostly in retreat in the Upper Nile front, they had gained ground on the Equatorian front where the SPLA was mostly restricted to its garrisons.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] This was attributed to local self-defence militias becoming increasingly integrated and the depopulation of towns resulting in the army having fewer supplies while the rebels were adapted to the bush.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] However, after the fall of the main rebel headquarters of Pagak in the summer, their southern headquarters in Lasu fell on 18 December 2017.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In late May, Kiir declared a unilateral ceasefire, which was taken with suspicion by others as it came after the late April government offensive that retook much territory and before the rainy season that would have reduced fighting.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Three days after the government retook Lasu it signed another ceasefire with the rebels.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The other major front of the conflict remained the Greater Upper Nile, where government forces mostly fought John Uliny's SPLA-IO allied Agwelek forces.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In a study of casualties up to April 2018, the deaths from violence peaked between 2016 and 2017.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In October 2016, the rebels attempted to take Malakal and by January 2017, fighting there had led to civilians deserting the country's second-largest city.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Whilst fighting in the Bahr el Ghazal region, pro-government militia Mathiang Anyoor attacked Wau killing up to 50 civilians in April 2017.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In the same month, the SPLA-IO captured Raja, the capital of Lol State, while state governor Hassan claimed the city was immediately retaken.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] A counteroffensive by the government starting in late April 2017 reversed most rebel gains, captured the capital of the Shilluk kingdom, Kodok, from Uliny and closed in on Pagak, which had been the SPLA-IO headquarters since 2014.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In July 2017, the SPLA along with forces loyal to Taban Deng Gai took over the rebel-held town of Maiwut.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The government took over Pagak in August 2017 while the SPLA-IO still held territory in traditional Nuer areas of Panyijar Country in Unity state and rural areas of Jonglei and Akobo state.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] SPLA-IO forces under Machar counterattacked Taban Deng Gai's force, in an attempt to retake Pagak.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] An additional dimension of the conflict developed with fighting between the opposition loyal to Machar and those supporting Taban Deng, largely within the Nuer-majority former state of Unity.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Observers felt that Kiir had given up on negotiations by talking with Taban Deng instead of Machar during the peace talks, as Taban was seen by many in the opposition as a traitor.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] As part of the "National Dialogue" initiated by Kiir in December 2016 where any former rebels who return to the capital would be given amnesty, about a dozen SPLM-IO officials defected to the government in January 2017.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Gabriel Tang, who was one of the generals to have defected from Machar during the peace talks in 2015, now allied with Lam Akol's largely Shilluk NDM and became its chief of staff.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In January 2017 Tang was killed in clashes with the SPLM-IO allied Agwelek forces led by John Uliny, a move the SPLM-IO described as a warning to rival rebel factions.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Two days later, Uliny's forces ambushed and killed Yohanis Okiech, destroying the Tiger Faction New Forces.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In February 2017, Deputy head of logistics, Lieutenant General Thomas Cirillo Swaka resigned, accusing Kiir of ethnic bias.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] This led to a series of high ranking resignations, including minister of Labour Lieutenant General Gabriel Duop Lam who also pledged allegiance to Machar.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Swaka formed a new rebel group called the National Salvation Front (NAS) in March 2017.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In March 2017, Cirillo, a Bari from Equatoria, got additional support as the SPLM-IO's Western Bahr al Ghazal commander, Faiz Ismail Futur, resigned to join the NAS while there are reports of six SPLM-IO shadow governors from Equatoria defecting to the NAS.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In the same month, head of the Cobra Faction Khalid Boutros dissolved the Cobra Faction and merged it with the NAS and claimed opposition groups were in consultation to unite their ranks.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In July 2017, John Kenyi Loburon, the SPLA-IO's commander of Central Equatoria state defected to the NAS, claiming favoritism towards Nuers in the SPLA-IO and then, as an NAS general in the same month, fought with the SPLA-IO in Central Equatoria in the first clashes between the two groups.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By November 2017, the NAS had captured areas in Kajo Keji from the SPLM-IO, before both groups were routed by the government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] With broad support at its inception, by 2018, many had come to view the NAS as "the Bari".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Cracks were appearing along clan lines among the ruling Dinka.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Kiir's Dinka of Warrap were in a feud with the Dinka of Paul Malong Awan's Aweil, who contributed the bulk of the government's fighting force in the war.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Around this time, the largely Dinka South Sudan Patriotic Army (SSPA) was formed in Northern Bahr el Ghazal, with the backing of powerful figures such as former presidential advisor Costello Garang Ring and allegedly Malong Awan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In May 2017, Kiir reduced the power of the chief of staff position and fired its powerful Dinka nationalist Malong Awan and replaced him with General James Ajongo Mawut, who was a Luo.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Awan left Juba with most of his Mathiang Anyoor militia while other militia members reportedly joined the SSPA.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By the end of 2017, the SSPA had claimed to have captured territory around Aweil and was seen as one of the biggest threats to Juba.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Awan was accused of plotting a rebellion and was detained but then released following pressure from the Dinka Council of Elders, a Dinka lobbying group.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] SPLM-IO rebels who were loyal to Malong Awan raided Juba in January 2018.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In April of that year, Awan announced the launch of a rebel group named South Sudan United Front (SS-UF), which claimed to push for federalism.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By March 2018, nine opposition groups, including the NAS, the NDM of Lam Akol, the FDP of Gabriel Chang, the SSPA of Costello Ring and the SSLM—but notably not including the SPLM-IO—had joined to form the South Sudan Opposition Alliance (SSOA) to collectively negotiate with the government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The United States put additional pressure on Juba by successfully passing an arms embargo on South Sudan in July 2018 through the UN Security Council, following their failure to do so in 2016, with Russia and China abstaining from voting this time.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Additionally, with neighboring Sudan facing economic troubles and relying on revenue from transporting oil from South Sudan, the Sudanese government, with a mix of incentives and coercion, brought Kiir and the SPLA-IO to hold talks in Khartoum.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The SPLM-IO protested when the Parliament, where the Kiir's party holds a majority of seats, extended the President's term and that of other officials by three years.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] An SSOA faction led by the NAS's Thomas Cirillo rejected the deal citing their small share in the power sharing agreement.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] As part of amnesty offered to groups following the peace deal, in August 2018, Brigadier General Chan Garang, claiming to lead a group of rebel soldiers from Malong's SS-UF, came back to the government along with 300 rebel soldiers in what was seen as a weakening of SS-UF.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In September 2018, Kiir signed a peace deal with Machar formally ending the five-year civil war.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Celebrations in Juba happened on 31 October 2018; however, there were criticisms that the peace deal failed to address the underlying issues of the conflict–the concentration of power in the hands of the president– and that the status quo will continue to produce violence.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] As part of the agreement, Machar was supposed to return to Juba in May to become a vice president again; citing security concerns, he asked for an extension of six months, which was accepted by Kiir.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Six months later, both sides agreed to delay the formation of a transitional unity government by 100 days.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The most contentious issue delaying the formation of the unity government was whether South Sudan should keep 32 or return to 10 states.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] On 14 February 2020, Kiir announced South Sudan would return to 10 states in addition to three administrative areas of Abyei, Pibor and Ruweng, and on 22 February Riek Machar was sworn in as first vice president for the creation of the unity government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The dissolution of parliament in order to bring a new parliament that shares power with the rebel groups, as called for by the 2018 peace deal, occurred in May 2021 after much delay.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The NAS became the main antagonist of the government, clashing with the government in the Central and Western part of Equatorial province starting in January 2019, leading to about 8,000 people fleeing Yei State.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The NAS and the FDP also alleged being attacked by the SPLM-IO in Upper Nile State.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The government continued to import arms.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In January 2020, the Community of Sant'Egidio mediated a peace declaration in Rome between the SSOMA and the South Sudanese government.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In August 2021, Simon Gatwech Dual, made the Kitgwang Declaration where he declared himself the new leader of the SPLM-IO.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Later in the month, clashes between forces loyal to Machar and Dual led to both sides reporting dozens of deaths.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In February 2025, Gatwech signed a peace agreement with president Kiir in which Gatwech's group would be integrated into the South Sudan People's Defence Forces.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Disarmament campaigns led by the government led to resistance, with clashes killing more than 100 people in two days in north-central Tonj in August 2020.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Localized inter-ethnic conflict reduced during the civil war but escalated in the last few years.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] It was argued that political elites bound by the deal have instead channeled weapons to community militias as a proxy war while others argued the power vacuum caused by the change in number of states is what led to the violence.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] While cattle raiding has been going on for years, some residents stated militias were targeting civilians more such as in one attack that killed 287 people in Uror County in May 2020.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In March 2025, the White Army attacked seized Nasir in the 2025 Nasir clashes killing an army general and attacking a UN helicopter killing a UN crew member.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The government responded with the help of intervention from Ugandan soldiers.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In December 2025, a coalition of rebel groups, including the White Army and those loyal to Machar, captured more areas of Jonglei.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] While the Nuer White Army was largely independent and decentralized, the government accused Machar of being behind the attacks.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Government forces entered Machar's residence in Juba and arrested him.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] This raised fears of a return to civil war and the UN reported that approximately 300,000 people had fled South Sudan in 2025, with about half of these refugees going to Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The SPLM-IO declared that Machar's arrest invalidated the 2018 peace deal, while the government insisted that it was still valid.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] *Foreign Policy* wrote that the deal had been deteriorating amid escalating conflict between the Dinka and Nuer, and was effectively ended by Machar's *de facto* removal from power.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The United Nations Mission in South Sudan has stated that the reported arrest "might lead the country to the brink of civil war".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] Earlier in 2022, the Nuer White Army had razed Shilluk villages before the government intervened with attack helicopters.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In 2025, John Uliny's Shilluk rebel group, the Agwelek Forces, agreed to integrate his forces into the national army.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] In January 2026, the government launched operation Enduring Peace to take back territory lost in Jonglei from the White Army and ordered civilians, non-government organisations and UN peacekeepers in three counties to evacuate.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] The United Nations stated that they would not comply.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] John Uliny and his forces were deployed in this operation and he was filmed ordering his troops to not spare civilians.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p02] By March 2026, the government claimed to have captured Akobo.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The government was accused by the US and aid groups among others of using starvation as a tactic of collective punishment for populations that supported the rebels by intentionally blocking aid.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Kiir's spokesman, claimed to a news conference, that rebel forces went into the hospital in Bor and killed 126 out of 127 patients.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Apparently an elderly man was blind and the rebels spared him.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] On 31 January 2014 in violation of the ceasefire agreement, government forces attacked Leer in Unity State, forcing 240 Staff and patients of Doctors Without Borders in Leer to flee into the bush.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Thousands of civilians fled to the bush.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Doctors Without Borders lost contact with two thirds of its staff formerly located in Leer.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] It is believed that the town was attacked by government troops as it is the home of former Vice President Riek Machar.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] On 18 April, UN said that at least 58 people were killed and more than 100 others wounded in an attack against one of its bases in South Sudan sheltering thousands of civilians.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] On 17 April 2014, 58 people were killed in an attack on the UN base in Bor.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Forty-eight of those killed were civilians, while 10 were among the attackers.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon emphasised that any attack on UN peacekeepers constituted "a war crime", while the UN Security Council expressed "outrage" at the attack.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In late 2016, in a government attack on Yei, three villages were destroyed with 3,000 homes burned in a single village.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Amnesty International claimed the army suffocated more than 60 people accused of supporting the opposition to death in a shipping container.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] There were ethnic undertones to the conflict with the SPLM and SPLA, which has been accused of being dominated by the Dinka.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] A Dinka lobbying group known as the "Jieng Council of Elders" was often accused of being behind hardline SPLM policies.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] While the army used to attract men from across tribes, during the war, the SPLA had largely been constituted of soldiers from the Dinka stronghold of Bahr el Ghazal, and the army was often referred to within the country as "the Dinka army".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Many of the worst atrocities committed were blamed on a group known as "Dot Ke Beny" (Rescue the President) or "Mathiang Anyoor" (brown caterpillar), while the SPLA claim that it is just another battalion.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Immediately after the alleged coup in 2013, Dinka troops, and particularly Mathiang Anyoor, were accused of carrying out pogroms, assisted by guides, in house to house searches of Nuer suburbs, while similar door to door searches of Nuers were reported in government held Malakal.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] About 240 Nuer men were killed at a police station in Juba's Gudele neighborhood.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The king of the Shilluk Kingdom, Kwongo Dak Padiet, claimed his people were at risk of physical and cultural extinction.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In the Equatoria region, Dinka soldiers were accused of targeting civilians on ethnic lines against the dozens of ethnic groups among the Equatorians.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Adama Dieng, the U.N.'s Special Adviser on the Prevention of Genocide, warned of genocide after visiting areas where there was fighting in Yei.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Khalid Boutros of the Cobra faction as well as officials of the Murle-led Boma State accuse the SPLA of aiding in attacks by Dinka from Jonglei state against the Boma state, and soldiers from Jonglei captured Kotchar in Boma in 2017.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The SPLM-IO is predominantly Nuer and its head, Machar, had previously committed the Bor massacre of mostly Dinka civilians in 1991.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In 2014, the Bentiu massacre occurred when Bentiu was recaptured by rebels April 2014 and 200 people were killed in a mosque.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Rebels separated the people and picked out those from opposing ethnic groups who they then executed.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Since the conflict began, more than 17,000 children were used in the conflict, with 1,300 recruited in 2016.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Reported incidents of sexual violence rose 60% in 2016, with Mundri in Equatoria's Amadi State being called the epicenter of the problem.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] A UN survey found that 70% of women who were sheltering in camps had been raped since the beginning of the conflict, with the vast majority of rapists being police and soldiers, and that 80% had witnessed someone else getting sexually assaulted.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The SPLA were reported to have recruited militias and young men in Unity state to take back rebel-held areas.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] They were given guns and their pay was what they could loot and the women they could rape.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Martell described the rampant sexual violence as not incidental to the war, but an integral and central part of the strategies of both sides, as "a tool for ethnic cleansing, as a means of humiliation and revenge".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Nor were foreign aid workers safe, with gunmen belonging to Kiir's Tiger Force stormed an UN relief camp at the Terrain Hotel on 11 July 2016, killed the journalist John Gatluak for being a Nuer, and proceeded to gang-rape five foreign aid workers as a "punishment" for foreign criticism of Kiir.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The UN peacekeepers from China who were supposed to be guarding the Terrain Hotel camp did nothing, despite being only a three-minute walk away from the hotel.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The UN's Special Envoy for Sexual Violence, Zainab Bangura, reported that nowhere in the world had she had ever seen a place with worse sexual violence than South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The same study also reported that rape was not only common against women and children, but also against men, though the reluctance of men to admit that they had been raped made it difficult to place a precise number on the cases of male rape.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] It has been argued that with increased tension with the UN and outside powers over the government's actions there was a new shift in violence by the government against foreign peacekeepers, aid workers and diplomats.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In July, soldiers ransacked a World Food Programme warehouse, stealing enough food to feed 220,000 people for a month, worth about $30 million.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In July, a rocket-propelled grenade was fired near a UN peacekeepers' vehicle with two Chinese peacekeepers dying after the government refused passage to a clinic sixteen kilometres (10 mi) away.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In December 2016, two staff members of the Norwegian Refugee Council were expelled from the country without a formal explanation.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In the deadliest attack on aid workers, six aid workers were killed in an ambush on 25 March 2017 bringing the number of aid workers killed since the start of the war to at least 79.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Violence came from the rebel side as well.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] On 26 August 2014, a UN Mi-8 cargo helicopter was shot down, killing three Russian crew members, and wounding another.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] This occurred nine days after rebel commander Peter Gadet threatened to shoot down UN aircraft, which he alleged were transporting government forces.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] During the first two days of fighting after 15 December, reports indicated that 66 soldiers had been killed in clashes in Juba, and at least 800 injured.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] By 23 December, the number of dead had likely surpassed 1,000, while an aid worker in the country estimated that the death toll was most likely in the tens of thousands.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The International Crisis Group reported on 9 January 2014 that up to 10,000 people were estimated to have died.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In November 2014, the International Crisis Group estimated the death toll could be between 50,000 and 100,000.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] A senior SPLA officer stated in November 2014 that the number of government soldiers killed and wounded topped 20,000, with 10,659 soldiers killed from January to October 2014 and 9,921 seriously wounded, according to a report by Radio Tamazuj.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] By March 2016, after more than two years of fighting, some aid workers and officials who did not want to speak on the record said the true figure might be as high as 300,000.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Two Indian UN peacekeepers were killed on 18 December when their base was stormed by rebels, and three US military Osprey aircraft were fired upon leading to four American service personnel being wounded.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] On 21 January 2014 Ankunda said that 9 Ugandan soldiers died in a rebel ambush at Gemeza a week before, and 12 others had been killed in total since 23 December.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] More than 4 million people have been displaced, with about 1.8 million internally displaced and about 2.5 million having fled to neighboring countries, especially Kenya, Sudan, and Uganda.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] This was the world's third-largest refugee population after Syria and Afghanistan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] About 86% of the refugees were women and children.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Uganda, which took more refugees in 2016 than all of those who crossed the Mediterranean into Europe, has had a notably generous policy.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Refugees are allowed to work and travel and families get a 30-metre by 30-metre plot of land to build a home with additional space for farming.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In just six months since being built, the Bidi Bidi Refugee Settlement in Uganda became the single largest refugee settlement on earth.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] However, the Ugandan government is seen as an ally of Kiir's crackdown on rebels, although with an increasing refugee population, Uganda has pressured Kiir to make peace.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The largest contingent of the Refugee Olympic Team at the 2016 Summer Olympics came from South Sudan, including its flag bearer.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] After the second Juba clashes, fighting intensified in the Equatoria region.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] As this is the agricultural heart of the country, the number of people facing starvation in the already food insecure nation soared to 6 million.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In February 2017, famine was declared in Unity state by the government and the United Nations, the first declaration of famine anywhere in the world in six years.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Days after the declaration of famine, the government raised the price of a business visa from $100 to $10,000, mostly aimed at aid workers, citing a need to increase government revenue.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In 2021, a "famine likely" announcement was made as not enough information was available to give a definite declaration of famine.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In 2018, Adama Dieng, the U.N. secretary-general's special adviser for the prevention of genocide accused Kenya and Uganda of funding the South Sudanese Civil War.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] According to Dieng "large quantities of weapons and ammunition were flowing into South Sudan through Kenya and Uganda".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The Kenyan government denied the accusations stating "The allegations by the senior UN official insinuating Kenya’s complicity in trafficking large quantities of weapons and ammunition into South Sudan, are not only unfortunate and misguiding, but lack facts".
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Israel has trained and sold weapons and surveillance systems to South Sudan after its independence in 2011, despite an arms embargo by the UN on the entire country.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Israeli-made weapons, including ACE assault rifles were seen used by South Sudanese soldiers.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Israel claims that these weapons were sold before the civil war occurred and that they have ceased selling offensive weapons in early 2014.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] These same rifles were used in December 2013 Nuer massacre.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Other rifles like the Micro Gali was reported to have been sold to Uganda in 2007, but the Ugandan government transferred those weapons to South Sudan without informing Israel.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In response to a meeting with a UN panel of experts after a UN report documented Israeli-made weapons in South Sudan, Israel assured that it had stopped selling offensive weapons.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Despite this, Israel continues to sell defensive equipment.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The supplied defensive equipment includes communications interception equipment, which has been used to eavesdrop and arrest opponents, including the targeting of journalists.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In June 2015, Israel welcomed South Sudanese officials to their Tel Aviv weapons expo.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] In 2017, a group of 54 Israeli activists filed a petition to the Israeli High Court seeking criminal investigation into Israel’s export of arms to South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] The goal was for more transparency on the arms deals that may have been involved in the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] A gag order was put on the petitions and the case.
[src:south-sudan/2013-south-sudanese-coup-d-état-attempt-p03] Freedom of information requests over the years regarding Israeli arms deals, contracts and training for South Sudan and related countries have been denied by the courts, ruling that this information was kept private from the public in order to protect the security of the nation.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Sudan was occupied by Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty in the 1800s and governed as an Anglo-Egyptian condominium from 1899 until Sudanese independence in 1956.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Following the First Sudanese Civil War, the Southern Sudan Autonomous Region was formed in 1972 and lasted until 1983.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Second Sudanese Civil War broke out in 1983 and ended in 2005 with the Comprehensive Peace Agreement.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Later that year, southern autonomy was restored when an Autonomous Government of Southern Sudan was formed.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan became an independent state on 9 July 2011, following 98.8% support for independence in a January 2011 referendum.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is the most recent sovereign state with widespread recognition as of 2026.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan descended into the South Sudanese Civil War from 2013 to 2018, enduring rampant human rights abuses, including forced displacement, ethnic massacres, and killings of journalists by various parties.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It has since been governed by a coalition formed by leaders of the former warring factions, Salva Kiir Mayardit (Sudan People's Liberation Movement or SPLM) and Riek Machar (Sudan People's Liberation Movement-in-Opposition or SPLM-IO).
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The South Sudanese population is composed mostly of Nilotic peoples spanning a variety of ethnic and linguistic groups.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is demographically among the youngest nations in the world, with roughly half its people under 18 years old.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The majority of inhabitants adhere to Christianity or various traditional indigenous faiths, with a sizeable Muslim minority.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan is a member of the United Nations, African Union, East African Community, and the Intergovernmental Authority on Development.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is one of the least developed countries in the world, ranking the lowest in the Human Development Index.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The South Sudanese economy has historically produced the world's lowest nominal GDP per capita.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The name *Sudan* is a name given to a geographical region to the south of the Sahara, stretching from Western Africa to eastern Central Africa.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The name derives from the Arabic **bilād as-sūdān** (بلاد السودان), or the "Land of the Blacks".
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The term was first used by Arab traders, historians and geographers.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Nilotic people of South Sudan—the Dinka, Anyuak, Bari, Acholi, Nuer, Shilluk, Kaligi (Arabic Feroghe), and others—first entered South Sudan sometime before the tenth century, coinciding with the fall of medieval Nubia.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] From the 15th to the 19th century, tribal migrations, largely from the area of Bahr el Ghazal, brought the Anyuak, Dinka, Nuer, and Shilluk to their modern locations in Bahr El Ghazal and the Upper Nile Region, while the Acholi and Bari settled in Equatoria.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Zande, Mundu, Avukaya and Baka, who entered South Sudan in the 16th century, established the region's largest state of Equatoria Region.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Of South Sudan's ethnic groups the Dinka are the largest, the Nuer the second-largest, the Azande the third-largest, and the Bari the fourth-largest.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] They are found in the Maridi, Yambio, and Tombura districts in the tropical rainforest belt of Western Equatoria, the Adio of Azande client in Yei, Central Equatoria, and Western Bahr el Ghazal.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In the 18th century, the Avungara sib rose to power over the rest of Azande society, a domination that continued into the 20th century.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] British colonial policy in Sudan had a long history of emphasising the development of the Arabised north and largely ignoring the non-Arabised south, which lacked schools, hospitals, roads, bridges, and other basic infrastructure.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] After Sudan's first independent elections in 1958, the continued neglect of the southern region by the Khartoum government led to uprisings, revolts, and the longest civil war on the continent.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] People affected by the violence included the Dinka, Nuer, Shilluk, Anyuak, Murle, Bari, Mundari, Baka, Balanda Bviri, Boya, Didinga, Jiye, Kakwa, Kaligi, Kuku, Lotuka, Nilotic, Toposa, and Zande.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Azande/Zande have had good relations with their neighbours, namely the Moru, Mundu, Pöjulu, Avukaya, Baka, and the small groups in Bahr el Ghazal, due to the expansionist policy of their king Gbudwe, in the 18th century.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In the 19th century, the Azande fought the French, the Belgians and the Mahdists to maintain their independence.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Ottoman Egypt, under the rule of Khedive Ismail Pasha, first attempted to control the region in the 1870s, establishing the province of Equatoria in the southern portion.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Egypt's first appointed governor was Samuel Baker, commissioned in 1869, followed by Charles George Gordon in 1874, and by Emin Pasha in 1878.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Mahdist Revolt of the 1880s destabilised the nascent province, and Equatoria ceased to exist as an Egyptian outpost in 1889.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Important settlements in Equatoria included Lado, Gondokoro, Dufile, and Wadelai.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] European colonial manoeuvrings in the region came to a head in 1898, when the Fashoda Incident occurred at present-day Kodok; Britain and France almost went to war over the region.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Britain then treated South Sudan as a distinct entity with a different stage of development than the North.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] This policy was legalised in 1930 by the announcement of the Southern Policy.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In 1946, without consulting Southern opinion, the British administration reversed its Southern Policy and began instead to implement a policy of uniting the North and the South.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] As a result, the country suffered serious neglect, a lack of infrastructure development, and major destruction and displacement.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] More than 2.5 million people have been killed, and millions more have become refugees both within and outside the country.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan has an estimated population of 12.7 million people in 2024, but, given the lack of a census in several decades, this estimate may be inaccurate.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The economy is predominantly rural and relies chiefly on subsistence farming.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Around 2005, the economy began a transition from this rural dominance, and urban areas within South Sudan have seen extensive development.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Between 9 and 15 January 2011, as a consequence of the Comprehensive Peace Agreement, the South Sudanese independence referendum was held to determine whether South Sudan should become an independent country, separate from Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Following that, 98.83% of those who took part in the referendum voted for separation or independence.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] On 23 January 2011, a steering committee on post-independence said the land would be named the Republic of Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Other names considered were Azania, Nile Republic, Kush Republic and even Juwama, a portmanteau for Juba, Wau and Malakal, three major cities.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan formally became independent from Sudan on 9 July, although certain disputes still remained, including the division of oil revenues, as 75% of all the former Sudan's oil reserves are in South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] As of March 2025, the region of Abyei still remains disputed.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] A separate referendum was to be held in Abyei on whether they want to join Sudan or South Sudan; however an official referendum was never held.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The South Kordofan conflict broke out in June 2011 between the Army of Sudan and the SPLA over the Nuba Mountains.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] On 9 July 2011, South Sudan became the 54th independent country in Africa (9 July is now celebrated as Independence Day, a national holiday) and since 14 July 2011, South Sudan is the 193rd member of the United Nations.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] On 27 July 2011, South Sudan became the 54th country to join the African Union.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In September 2011, Google Maps recognised South Sudan as an independent country, after a massive crowdsourcing mapping initiative was launched.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In 2011 it was reported that South Sudan was at war with at least seven armed groups in 9 of its 10 states, with tens of thousands displaced.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The fighters accuse the government of plotting to stay in power indefinitely, not fairly representing and supporting all tribal groups while neglecting development in rural areas.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) also operates in a wide area that includes South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Inter-ethnic warfare in some cases predates the war of independence and is widespread.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In December 2011, tribal clashes intensified between the Nuer White Army of the Lou Nuer and the Murle.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The White Army warned it would wipe out the Murle and would also fight South Sudanese and UN forces sent to the area around Pibor.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In March 2012, South Sudanese forces seized the Heglig oil fields in lands claimed by both Sudan and South Sudan in the province of South Kordofan after conflict with Sudanese forces in the South Sudanese state of Unity.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan withdrew on 20 March, and the Sudanese Army entered Heglig two days later.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] On 5 September 2013, an article written by analyst Duop Chak Wuol was published by the US-based South Sudan News Agency (SSNA).
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The writer raised critical questions surrounding what he described as the rise of autocracy within the top leadership of the Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) and warned of monumental repercussions unless the ruling elites restored the founding principles of the party.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Duop also berated the ruling party, arguing that the party has replaced its founding principles with "forgotten promises and deceptions".
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In December 2013, a political power struggle broke out between President Kiir and his former deputy Riek Machar, as the president accused Machar and ten others of attempting a coup d'état.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Fighting broke out, igniting the South Sudanese Civil War.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Ugandan troops were deployed to fight alongside South Sudanese government forces against the rebels.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Numerous ceasefires were mediated by the Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD) between the Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) and SPLM – in opposition and were subsequently broken.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] A peace agreement was signed in Ethiopia under threat of United Nations sanctions for both sides in August 2015.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Machar returned to Juba in 2016 and was appointed vice-president.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Following a second break-out of violence in Juba, Machar was replaced as vice-president and he fled the country as the conflict erupted again.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Rebel in-fighting has become a major part of the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Rivalry among Dinka factions led by the President and Malong Awan has also led to fighting.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In August 2018, another power-sharing agreement came into effect.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] About 400,000 people are estimated to have been killed in the war, including notable atrocities such as the 2014 Bentiu massacre.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Although both men have supporters from across South Sudan's ethnic divides, subsequent fighting has been communal, with rebels targeting members of Kiir's Dinka ethnic group and government soldiers attacking Nuers.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] More than 4 million people have been displaced, with about 1.8 million of those internally displaced, and about 2.5 million having fled to neighbouring countries, especially Uganda and Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] On 20 February 2020, Salva Kiir Mayardit and Riek Machar agreed to a peace deal; further, a national unity government on 22 February 2020, as Machar was sworn in as the First Vice-President of the country.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Despite the official cessation of the civil war, violence between armed militia groups at the community level has continued in the country; according to Yasmin Sooka, Chair of the Commission of Human Rights in Sudan, the level of violence "far exceeds the violence between 2013 and 2019".
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan acceded to the Treaty of the East Africa Community on 15 April 2016 and became a full member on 15 August 2016.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan, Democratic Republic of Congo and Federal Republic of Somalia are the newest members of the East African Community.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The first democratic elections in South Sudan since the start of the civil war were scheduled for 2023 by the peace agreement that ended the war officially, but the transitional government and opposition agreed in 2022 to move them to late 2024 instead.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In September 2024, Kiir's office announced that the elections would be postponed an additional two years, to December 2026.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In 2025, violence expanded across South Sudan as ceasefire violations and fighting between government forces and opposition groups intensified in Jonglei, Unity, and Upper Nile states.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Aerial bombardments, river based operations, ambushes, and retaliatory attacks were reported.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] These incidents resulted in civilian casualties, displacement, and the loss of livelihoods.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In early March, clashes between the Army and the rebel Nuer White Army in the town of Nasir left dozens dead.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] On 26 March 2025, Vice-President Riek Machar was arrested on orders of President Salva Kiir claiming he had instigated and supported the White Army, despite the White Army denying any ties.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The arrest was met by a response from the SPLM-IO stating such an act violates the ceasefire that ended the South Sudanese civil war in 2020.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Machar's arrest was accompanied by the mass sacking of his supporters, and the arrival of a unit from the Ugandan armed forces invited into the country by Kiir to help fight against the White Army.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres stated that the "peace agreement is in shambles" and South Sudan is on "the edge of a collapse into civil war" while the African Union has sent a delegation to try to deescalate the conflict.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] At least 169 people were killed and 50 injured in March 2026 when armed youth from Unity State attacked Abiemnom County in the Ruweng Administrative Area.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The attackers burned markets and homes before being driven out by the army, after which local authorities regained control.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The killings form part of a growing surge in violence across South Sudan, where forces aligned with President Salva Kiir are fighting armed groups believed to support opposition leader Riek Machar.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan lies between latitudes 3° and 13°N, and longitudes 24° and 36°E.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is covered in tropical forest, swamps, and grassland.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The White Nile passes through the country, passing by Juba.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Sudd is formed by the White Nile, known locally as the *Bahr al Jabal*, meaning "Mountain Sea".
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan's protected area of Bandingilo National Park hosts the second-largest wildlife migration in the world.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Surveys have revealed that Boma National Park, west of the Ethiopian border, as well as the Sudd wetland and Southern National Park near the border with Congo, provided habitat for large populations of hartebeest, kob, topi, buffalo, elephants, giraffes, and lions.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan's forest reserves also provided habitat for bongo, giant forest hogs, red river hogs, forest elephants, chimpanzees, and forest monkeys.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Surveys begun in 2005 by WCS in partnership with the semi-autonomous government of Southern Sudan revealed that significant, though diminished wildlife populations still exist, and that, astonishingly, the huge migration of 1.3 million antelopes in the southeast is substantially intact.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Habitats in the country include grasslands, high-altitude plateaus and escarpments, wooded and grassy savannas, floodplains, and wetlands.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Associated wildlife species include the endemic white-eared kob and Nile Lechwe, as well as elephants, giraffes, common eland, giant eland, oryx, lions, African wild dogs, cape buffalo, and topi (locally called tiang).
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Little is known about the white-eared kob and tiang, both types of antelope, whose migrations were legendary before the civil war.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Boma-Jonglei Landscape region encompasses Boma National Park, broad pasturelands and floodplains, Bandingilo National Park, and the Sudd, a vast area of swamp and seasonally flooded grasslands that includes the Zeraf Wildlife Reserve.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Little is known of the fungi of South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] A list of fungi in Sudan was prepared by S.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Tarr and published by the then Commonwealth Mycological Institute (Kew, Surrey, UK) in 1955.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The list, of 383 species in 175 genera, included all fungi observed within the then boundaries of the country.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Many of those records relate to what is now South Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Most of the species recorded were associated with diseases of crops.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The true number of species of fungi in South Sudan is probably much higher.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In 2006, President Kiir announced that his government would do everything possible to protect and propagate South Sudanese fauna and flora, and seek to reduce the effects of wildfires, waste dumping, and water pollution.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The environment is threatened by the development of the economy and infrastructure.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The country had a 2019 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 9.45/10, ranking it fourth globally out of 172 countries.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Several ecoregions extend across South Sudan: the East Sudanian savanna, Northern Congolian forest–savanna mosaic, Saharan flooded grasslands (Sudd), Sahelian Acacia savanna, East African montane forests, and the Northern Acacia–Commiphora bushlands and thickets.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan has a tropical climate, characterised by a rainy season of high humidity and large amounts of rainfall followed by a drier season.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The temperature on average is always high with July being the coolest month with average temperatures falling between 20 and 30 °C (68 and 86 °F) and March being the warmest month with average temperatures ranging from 23 to 37 °C (73 to 98 °F).
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The most rainfall is seen between May and October, but the rainy season can commence in April and extend until November.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The season is "influenced by the annual shift of the Inter-Tropical Zone" and the shift to southerly and southwesterly winds leading to slightly lower temperatures, higher humidity, and more cloud coverage.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] One study has showed that climate change is expected to increase rainfall rates over South Sudan, but there is greater uncertainty about whether the number of rainy days will increase or decrease.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan includes the Sudd, one of the world's largest wetlands.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The total area under protection is around 143,000 km2 (55,000 sq mi) spread over 23 protected areas which account for 15% of the South Sudanese territory.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The largest protected area is the Sudd Wetland, which is an important bird life area covering 57,000 km2 (22,000 sq mi).
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is also a Ramsar Site with over 400 bird species, 100 mammal species, and 100 fish species.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Many of the protected areas are exploited for illegal hunting and rearing of livestock.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan's protected areas are in the flood plains of the Nile River.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The habitat predominantly comprises grasslands, high-altitude plateaus and escarpments, wooded and grassy savannas, floodplains and wetlands.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The now defunct Southern Sudan Legislative Assembly ratified a transitional constitution shortly before independence on 9 July 2011.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The constitution was signed by the President of South Sudan, Salva Kiir Mayardit, on Independence Day and thereby came into force.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is now the supreme law of the land, superseding the Interim Constitution of 2005.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The constitution establishes a presidential system of government headed by a president who is head of state, head of government, and commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It also establishes the National Legislature comprising two houses: a directly elected assembly, the National Legislative Assembly, and a second chamber of representatives of the states, the Council of States.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] John Garang, one of the founders of the SPLA/M, was the president of the autonomous government until his death on 30 July 2005.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Salva Kiir Mayardit, his deputy, was sworn in as First Vice-President of Sudan and President of the Government of Southern Sudan on 11 August 2005.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Riek Machar replaced him as Vice-President of the Government.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Legislative power is vested in the government and the bicameral National Legislature.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The constitution also provides for an independent judiciary, the highest organ being the Supreme court.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] On 8 May 2021, South Sudanese president Salva Kiir announced a dissolution of Parliament as part of a 2018 peace deal to set up a new legislative body that will number 550 lawmakers.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] According to 2023 V-Dem Democracy indices South Sudan is third lowest ranked electoral democracy in Africa.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The capital of South Sudan is located at Juba, which is also the state capital of Central Equatoria and the county seat of the eponymous Juba County, and is the country's largest city.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] However, due to Juba's poor infrastructure and massive urban growth, as well as its lack of centrality within South Sudan, the South Sudanese Government adopted a resolution in February 2011 to study the creation of a new planned city to serve as the seat of government.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It was planned that the capital city would be changed to the more centrally located Ramciel.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] This proposal is functionally similar to construction projects in Abuja, Nigeria; Brasília, Brazil; and Canberra, Australia; among other modern-era planned national capitals.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is unclear how the government will fund the project.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In September 2011, a spokesman for the government said the country's political leaders had accepted a proposal to build a new capital at Ramciel, a place in Lakes state near the borders with Central Equatoria and Jonglei.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Ramciel is considered to be the geographical centre of the country, and the late pro-independence leader John Garang allegedly had plans to relocate the capital there before his death in 2005.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The proposal was supported by the Lakes state government and at least one Ramciel tribal chief.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The design, planning, and construction of the city was supposed to take as many as five years, government ministers said, and the move of national institutions to the new capital was supposed to be implemented in stages.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] As of 2024, the relocation project is stalled.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The terms of a peace agreement signed on 22 February 2020, South Sudan is divided into ten states, with two administrative areas and one area with special administrative status.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Kafia Kingi area is disputed between South Sudan and Sudan and the Ilemi Triangle is disputed between South Sudan and Kenya.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Since independence, relations with Sudan have been changing.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Sudan's President Omar al-Bashir first announced, in January 2011, that dual citizenship in the North and the South would be allowed, but upon the independence of South Sudan he retracted the offer.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] He has also suggested an EU-style confederation.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Essam Sharaf, Prime Minister of Egypt after the 2011 Egyptian Revolution, made his first foreign visit to Khartoum and Juba in the lead-up to South Sudan's secession.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Israel quickly recognised South Sudan as an independent country, and is host to thousands of refugees from South Sudan, many of whom have finally been granted temporary resident status more than a decade later.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] According to American sources, President Obama officially recognised the new state after Sudan, Egypt, Germany and Kenya were among the first to recognise the country's independence on 8 July 2011.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Several states that participated in the international negotiations concluded with a self-determination referendum were also quick to acknowledge the overwhelming result.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The Rationalist process included Kenya, Uganda, Egypt, Ethiopia, Libya, Eritrea, the United Kingdom and Norway.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan is a member state of the United Nations, the African Union, the East African Community, and the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan plans to join the Commonwealth of Nations, the International Monetary Fund, OPEC+, and the World Bank.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Some international trade organisations categorise South Sudan as part of the Greater Horn of Africa.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Full membership in the Arab League has been assured, should the country's government choose to seek it, though it could also opt for observer status.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It was admitted to UNESCO on 3 November 2011.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] On 25 November 2011, it officially joined the Intergovernmental Authority on Development, a regional grouping of East African states.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The United States supported the 2011 referendum on South Sudan's independence.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Given the interdependence between some sectors of the economy of the Republic of South Sudan and the Republic of Sudan, certain activities still require OFAC authorisation.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Absent a licence, current Sudanese sanction regulations will continue to prohibit US persons from dealing in property and interests that benefit Sudan or the Government of Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] A 2011 Congressional Research Service report, "The Republic of South Sudan: Opportunities and Challenges for Africa's Newest Country", identifies outstanding political and humanitarian issues as the country forges its future.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In July 2019, UN ambassadors of 37 countries, including South Sudan, signed a joint letter to the UNHRC defending China's treatment of Uyghurs in the Xinjiang region.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The UAE lent South Sudan $12 billion for a period of 20 years.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The loan agreement was signed between South Sudan and an Emirati firm owned by Hamad bin Khalifa Al Nahyan, the sources of whose wealth and investments have been suspicions during the failed takeover of Beitar Jerusalem FC.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The loan deposit was directed to an Emirati bank account, of which 70% were allocated to infrastructure facilities.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] As per the agreement, South Sudan was to repay by the means of oil shipments, priced at $10 per barrel less than its market value.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Additional oil shipments were agreed in case of decrease in oil prices.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The agreement took no account of the Sudan war.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] A defence paper was initiated in 2007 by then Minister for SPLA Affairs Dominic Dim Deng, and a draft was produced in 2008.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It declared that Southern Sudan would eventually maintain land, air, and riverine forces.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] As of 2015, South Sudan has the third highest military spending as a percentage of GDP in the world, behind only Oman and Saudi Arabia.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Campaigns of atrocities against civilians have been attributed to the SPLA.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In the SPLA/M's attempt to disarm rebellions among the Shilluk and Murle, they burned scores of villages, raped hundreds of women and girls and killed an untold number of civilians.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Civilians alleging torture claim fingernails being torn out, burning plastic bags dripped on children to make their parents hand over weapons, and villagers burned alive in their huts if it was suspected that rebels had spent the night there.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In May 2011, the SPLA allegedly set fire to over 7,000 homes in Unity State.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] At the beginning of 2017, genocide was imminent again.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Ethnic violence intensified after South Sudan's independence, as unresolved grievances, weak governance, and political rivalry contributed to growing instability.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] After fighting broke out in December 2013, armed groups attacked civilians on ethnic grounds.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Peter Abdul Rahaman Sule, the leader of the key opposition group United Democratic Forum, has been under arrest since 3 November 2011 over allegations linking him to the formation of a new rebel group fighting against the government.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Recruitment of child soldiers has also been cited as a serious problem in the country.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In April 2014, Navi Pillay, then the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, stated that more than 9,000 child soldiers had been fighting in South Sudan's civil war.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In March 2016, the UN reported that the South Sudan Army was being paid not in money but with a "do what you can and take what you can" policy that allowed them to confiscate cattle and other possessions, and even to rape and murder civilian women as a form of salary.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The report described all sides but especially the South Sudan government SPLA forces and allied militia making targeted attacks on civilians based on ethnicity, systematically destroying towns and villages.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Violence against women is common in the country, and South Sudan's laws and policies have been criticised as inadequate in offering protection.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In 2010, the child marriage rate in southern Sudan was 52%.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is driven by socioeconomic factors such as poverty and gender inequality.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Child marriage in South Sudan is associated with elevated maternal mortality and higher rates of school dropout.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] Economic and legal constraints under customary law make it difficult for women to get a divorce.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The economy of South Sudan is one of the world's most underdeveloped, with South Sudan having little existing infrastructure and the highest maternal mortality and female illiteracy rates in the world as of 2011.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] South Sudan exports timber to the international market.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The region also contains many natural resources such as petroleum, iron ore, copper, chromium ore, zinc, tungsten, mica, silver, gold, diamonds, hardwoods, limestone and hydropower.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The country's economy, as in many other developing countries, is heavily dependent on agriculture.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The oilfields in South Sudan have been significant to the economy since the latter part of the 20th century.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] In 2023, oil constitutes more than 90% of state revenues.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The country has the third-largest oil reserves in Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] However, after South Sudan became an independent nation in July 2011, southern and northern negotiators were not immediately able to reach an agreement on how to split the revenue from these southern oilfields.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] It is estimated that South Sudan has around 4 times the oil deposits of Sudan.
[src:south-sudan/south-sudan-p01] The oil revenues, according to the Comprehensive Peace Agreement (CPA), were split equally for the duration of the agreement period.
